She sat on the floor another 10minutes or so, then moved to a chair where she was monitor approximately 15 more minutes.   She stated at that time that she was feeling "fine", "back to normal" .   She chose to leave at that time, but on request, called the pharmacy within about 35minutes to report that she arrived safely home and still felt fine.  At 2pm, she was contacted to  confirm information for this submission and again stated she felt fine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient reports shoulder pain that radiates up neck.

At about 2:35pm, 15 minutes post vaccination, patient was seated and leaned forward.  She did not lose consciousness, but appeared pale.  She stated she felt weak and dizzy.  A cot and privacy was provided for patient.  Patient states she did not eat or drink that morning so 8 ounces of juice was provided along with a cereal bar.  Oxygen saturation remained WNL at this time and throughout the episode.  At 2:40pm BP was 145/82.  2:44pm = 142/86.  2:46 = 148/84.  2:47pm = sat up on edge of cot.  2:55pm = 142/94.  2:57 = standing.  Patient walked around at 3:00pm.  HR remained WNL throughout the entire episode.  Patient refused hospital/ambulance transfer.  3:05 = patient states she feels well enough to drive home.  Patient refused help with transportation.  5:00pm on March 19 (same day), writer called patient for follow up.  Patient states she feels better but still some feelings of dizziness and weakness.  Patient was advised to reach out to her PCP for his or her awareness and/or recommendations.  Patient was also advised if symptoms progress to call PCP office for triage or head to ER if necessary.  Follow up call was placed on 3/23/21 at 10:30am.  Patient states she felt weak and dizzy throughout the weekend and Monday, but states today she is at baseline.

not quite 2 days later, i started having trouble breathing, and i had not had any symptoms of the asthma or the COPD because i only experience trouble breathing after a case of the flu or a severe cold, which always leads to congestion, and often pneumonia.   There was constant coughing and gasping for air, a tightness in my chest.  I went online to see if there were any other people who had experienced this, and the literature was saying the problems with breathing usually start within a few hours, but mine took longer and I know it was related to the vaccine.  I was given  an ADVAIR inhaler which did nothing to alleviate the symptoms, so then had 3 weeks of prednisone, to the point i did not want to go for the second dose, but my doctor talked me into it as I have so many pre-existing conditions.  I had no problem at all with the second dose and am now off the prednisone and the advair
LAB_DATA: none, i don't think my doctor felt it was directly a cause and effect situation....but i do.  i live in this body.  i NEVER EVER EVER had asthma or copd symptoms unless I got sick with the cold or the flu and always I have to go on prednisone to clear the gunk out of my lungs.  THIS WAS COMPLETELY DIFFERENT.  I HAD NO GUNK IN MY LUNGS.  THIS WAS A CONSTANT, DRY COUGH, WITH TIGHTNESS IN MY CHEST TO THE POINT I COULD NOT WALK WITHOUT GASPING FOR AIR.  IT WAS SCARY AND I HAVE NEVER HAD THIS HAPPEN TO ME MY ENTIRE LIFE
HISTORY: diabetes,  and asthma and copd only when i get the flu or pneumonia

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Experienced severe pain in the right shoulder/bicep area, the opposite arm from the injection (injection was given in the left arm). After speaking with a friend who is a doctor, they mentioned Parsonage Turner Syndrome and Brachial neuritis, all the symptoms match the discriptions of those. I immediately started using a Tens unit to help stimulate the shoulder and arm area, began ice treatment and taking tylenol for the pain. The doctor in the office I work at after listening to the issue and symptoms said the same thing and started me on Gabapentin to help with the nerve pain and is going to continue to monitor the symptoms. It has been 46 days since getting the 2nd shot, and I have been at a 8 to a 9 out of 10 pain-wise almost 24/7, it has affected my ability to work and i have had to call in a few days because of the pain and being unable to use my right arm proficiently (I am right handed), it has affected my family and my ability to get things done around the house and engage my children and it has affected my ability to get a good sleep.

She did have tingling and numbness in her fingers, but nothing in her feet, and did not extend beyond her face and cheeks.  Then 20 minutes later at 1:55 PM her tongue became sort of thick and a little numb, but did not swell.   The area between her tongue and mouth tightened and her jaw tightened but nothing swelled.  No itching in the throat.  She had some sort of aching like menstrual cramps but has had a hysterectomy.  She did also have a headache, took a Tylenol at 2:15 and went to sleep.  When she woke up had fatigue, sore arm, and everything else had passed other than the lips feeling prickly and numb.  The tongue was no longer tight or in the jaw.  Just still had the open sinuses and the headache.  The most significant thing was the thickness and lack of feeling of her tongue.   By Saturday she was fine other than the normal side effects, soreness of arm, no red rash, but had been  moving it around.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After the shot, I had the "typical" reaction - sore arm, a bit of a head ache, but nothing concerning.  Then on the 4th night after my shot, I started feeling bad and got in bed.  That night I couldn't sleep due to not feeling well. The next morning I was very dizzy, agitated, nauseous and had a weird head ache behind my eyes.    I started feeling like I was going to throw up anytime I looked at anything for more than about a minute. (my phone, a book, a puzzle, the tv).   I laid by the toilet most of the day with a wash cloth over my eyes. Around 6pm that night I started throwing up a TON, major headache, body aches, shivers, but no fever.   These symptoms lasted for the next two days.  (as a side note, this was during the freeze, so I was not able to call my doctor, etc...).  I started feeling better on day 4 but I had a headache for about two week - that still lingers on most days.  (headaches are unusual for me).  This was, without a doubt, the sickest I have ever been in my life! I decided not to get the 2nd shot because I was afraid of feeling worse after the 2nd shot.
LAB_DATA: None were done - My symptoms where during the freeze. No doctors were available.
OTHER_MEDS: zyrtek, B-12 vit, Vit D, Vit C, and Pristiq
ALLERGIES: Allergic to melon's and egg whites

After vaccination with MenACYW #2, Men B #2, HPV #3, Pt stated he felt lightheaded. CMA advised him to remain seated while she disposed of sharps. He began to stand up from the exam table then proceeded to slide down the side of the exam table and collapsed, hitting the right side of his head on the ground. After approx. 15 seconds he began to sit up. After CMA called for help, MD ran into the room and assisted patient off floor as he was trying to stand up and into a chair. Lead CMA instructed to bring a wheelchair and clear procedure room. CMA instructed to gather vitals cart. Patient rubbing left side of his head and saying he "blacked out" and did not remember falling. No pallor, increased WOB noted. Last reported memory was feeling dizzy after vaccines. Patient's head examined in exam room, no lacerations, bleeding, bruising, abrasions, or other signs of trauma noted. MD assisted Pt into wheelchair and lead CMA transported him to procedure room. Patient assisted into chair by MD and advised to lay supine. MD remained at patient's side throughout the remainder of the visit. Initial VS obtained as follows: BP 90/58, HR 58, no increased WOB. SBP 2nd and DBP 28th percentile for sex, age, and height. Lead CMA instructed to get a sugary drink and patient's father from the car and CMA advised to check blood glucose and get Vietnamese phone interpreter. Lead CMA returned with cold Sprite; patient advised to take a few sips which he did. Advised lead CMA to inform PM. BG checked and was 145. Pt then reported pain in his left clavicle and that he "think I broke it." Denies h/o previous clavicle trauma or displacement, previous syncopal episode. Reports he did not eat breakfast this morning. Clavicles exposed and examined. Distal Left clavicle internally displaced anteriorly by 0.5-1 cm, no broken skin, bruising or other skin changes, no crepitus noted. Gentle ROM of left shoulder elicited pain, no other abnormalities on upper extremity MSK, neurovascular exam noted. PULM exam CTA b/l in upper lobes, CV exam RRR w/o m/r/g. VS rechecked and was 123/73, HR 71. Pt reported feeling better and wanted to walk but he was advised to remain in the chair and continue drinking Sprite. Explained how Pt was doing to dad, the events leading up to his fall, confirmed his PMH, and apologized for what happened through medically certified Vietnamese phone interpreter. Addressed his questions about what vaccines were given (MenACYW #2, Men B #2, HPV #3), confirmed COVID vaccine was not given, explained normalized VS and blood glucose, explained likely vasovagal etiology of syncope and fall, and explained need for immediate evaluation by orthopedics for imaging and stabilization of left clavicle. Offered dad the option to go to clinic directly or ED, he preferred clinic. Confirmed a STAT order for ortho evaluation was being sent to clinic and he would be provided a copy of the address. Also advised dad I will be notifying VAERS about Pt's syncopal episode, and that he may do so as well. VIS for each vaccine with VAERS contact info, clinic address provided. F/u with ortho as directed, may return to school per ortho instructions. Informed dad I will have CMA call tomorrow to check on Pt, he agreed to call. After Pt felt better after 25 minutes and Dad's questions answered to his satisfaction, patient assisted into wheelchair by MD and assisted into car by MD which dad had pulled into the bay. Patient transported directly to clinic. CMA instructed to call clinic and inform them of patient's injury, VS, glucose, and need for medically certified Vietnamese interpreter.
LAB_DATA: Initial VS obtained as follows: BP 90/58, HR 58, no increased WOB. SBP 2nd and DBP 28th percentile for sex, age, and height. VS rechecked and was 123/73, HR 71. -BG 145; Severely angulated Left clavicle fracture w/ end to end apposition on ED X-ray per orthopedics consult note on 3/22/21. Surgery (ORIF) scheduled 3/25/21.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Right after I received my vaccine I was told to pull up and wait 15 minutes. After about 2 minutes I started to feel hot and noticed my arm was red. Ochsner had me pull over by the EMT tent and I waited 45 additional minutes to see if I had any other effects. The rash didn't go away but I didn't itch and I wasn't uncomfortable. It was just a surface rash. The rash was completely gone by 10PM that same night. I woke up at 2AM that same night/early the next morning and the whole left side of my body was numb and felt very heavy. I also had a very mild fever and cold like symptoms. These symptoms included chills, dizziness, fatigue, and headaches. All of my symptoms, including the pain and heaviness on my left side, were gone the following morning which was about 36 hours after first receiving the vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Later that evening after the vaccine I noticed a rash had developed on my left arm which proceeded around the left arm, across my back, chest and little dots on my neck. A blister/skin tag developed under my breast area which is still there today. I took a zyrtec  which caused some of the smaller red spots to disappear but the large red spot on my arm remained.  When I used deodorant I developed a rash under both arms so I reached out to my Dermatologist who prescibed a steroid cream and  advised I take 2 doses of the zyrtec.  That didnt help so I was now advised take a zytec/pepid bid and 2benedryl at night.  I to date still have to bath with oatmeal and baking soda because the itching gets so bad at times. On 1/27 the rash spread to the inner thighs, groin, abdomen area and was then prescribed a 10 day oral predinisone pack which did reduce the rash but the rash still remained in various areas, but once I stopped the steroid around 2/20 the rash came back and was even worse. I am still experiencing the rash to date and it is still super itchy.  I had 2 biospys in the beginning Feb which came back as T-Cell  Infiltrate and was advised it could be scabies. On 3/4 I had another biospy done by another Dermatologist and 3/22 I was diagnosed with Dermatitis Folliculitis and placed on antibiotics today and I have a follow up scheduled within the next 3 weeks
ALLERGIES: penicillin, metals, seasonal allergies, mold, mildew and dust mites

I felt light headedness right away. The night that I got the injection, I felt kind of drunk. I felt like I had too much alcohol. I am very sensitive to things. I felt silly - loose - tired.  In the night, I had aches and chills - no fever. The next day I felt achy and really really tired. I had a pain at the injection site. That evolved into a left side migraine (the achiness and fatigue and pain from shot) It created tension up my arm and up my neck - and I did get nausea with the headache - on Saturday. Sunday, I felt a little bit better but energy was still low - unusual tiredness; couldn't exercise as I felt a heavy fatigue. On Sunday, I went to a dance class but it was difficult as I was tired. On Monday, I felt a tiny bit better but still fatigued and did another dance class which went a little better. On Monday evening, I felt like I did the night of the injection - a little loopy and "drunk like." Monday night, I woke up with a Fiery, achy, itchy, burning rash on both of my arms and the tops of my legs. If I would itch it, it would exaggerate it. When I woke up the next day - the rash went everywhere in my body - it would come and go in different places - neck, face, down and up my legs and feet and on my butt. Pretty much every spot had the rash at one time or another. It was really bad on Tuesday morning, I called the doctor. Was treated with Benadryl and cortisone cream which helped with the symptoms. Tuesday night, it was excruciating - it was all up and down my legs, arms, neck and face and stomach and rear end and feet. It was very achy, burning and itchy - very intense. It would hurt if I scratched it. Accompanied with really intense fatigue. Wednesday, after taking Benadryl, I woke up and it was a tiny bit better. It was still on my legs, neck and face. Sometimes my arms would flare up and sometimes they wouldn't. Any kind of exertion - like my dance class - would trigger the rash - so I took a break from exercising that week.  It started getting incrementally better - very slowly. Still there on Thursday - still fatigued and I was still taking Benadryl. Friday, also. Saturday, it was pretty much gone but it would threaten to come back and I felt itchiness in my legs when I went for a walk. It still feels a little lingering - my legs are itchy. I'm still building back my energy. Incrementally my energy is increasing. Still not 100% there but it's getting better day by day.  Note: My history with my skin: I do get flare ups when I get bug bites and when I get poison ivy - I have very sensitive skin.
OTHER_MEDS: At tale end of regimen of Isoniazid - as I had tested positive of latent TB (no symptoms); Vit B6; Vitamin - Prenatal Vitamin
ALLERGIES: no - I have very sensitive skin

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient came to Vaccination Clinic to receive first dose of Pfizer vaccine on 3/15/2021. Patient was vaccinated at 1147 and began to walk toward EMT monitoring area at 1153. While the patient was walking, the patient reported feeling faint. RN, followed the patient from behind. RN noticed patient beginning to fall and was able to catch her using her leg as support and guided patient to the floor. Both RN and patient decline sustaining any injuries related to this event. When on the floor, patient appeared pale, had cold and clammy hands, and was diaphoretic. RN assisted the patient by holding her legs in the air while the patient layed on her back. Patient was A&Ox4 at 1155 with a BP of 121/76. At 1159, patient reported feeling "better" and was transferred to zero-gravity chair. The patient's blood pressure was reassessed at 1201, 1221, and 1227 and reported to be 124/81, 122/74, and 125/79, respectively. The patient refused transport via EMS and stated she preferred to drive herself home. Patient able to ambulate without assistance. Patient left to her car at 1230. Upon departure, patient was ambulatory, A&Ox4, with no reports of trouble breathing, dizziness, or lightheadedness. The patient was given education related to when to seek medical care, including shortness of breath, chest tightness, and sensation of throat tightness. The patient was provided with additional guidance on what to do when receiving a second dose, including notifying the nurse that she has had a history of fainting.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Small clusters of reddish pink bumps/hives, some raised and some under skin on torso (neck, shoulder, back, stomach, hip).  Most are itchy but some are not.  I noticed a cluster of 3 bumps/hives on the right shoulder when I returned home and then checked the rest of my body.  There were other small clusters and some single bumps (~ 15 bumps in total).  In the evening on 3/20/21, my left check felt itchy and the back of my scalp near the neck was itchy and pink.  The next morning on 3/21/21 another cluster of 7 bumps/hives appeared on my back and a few other single bumps on my back.  I took one Benadryl tab the night of 3/21 plus used Benadryl cream on the bumps/hives.  On 3/22, I called my insurance 24 hour nurse line for advice.  I was advised to keep taking the Benadryl as needed to try to lower the potential histamine response plus drinking lots of water.  We reviewed the CDC guidance and we agreed my issue did not meet the criteria to prevent taking the second Moderna dose at this time since the bumps/rash was only topical and I did not experience swelling or wheezing in addition to the bumps/hives.  As of today 3/23, the bumps have not gone away and are still itchy.  They appear to be darker in color.  I will continue to use the proposed Benadryl protocol I described and plan to start the same regimen preventively after I get the second dose in ~ 4 weeks.
OTHER_MEDS: Progesterone caps 100mg daily Estradiol tabs 1Mg daily Testosterone cream 1.5mg/gm (2 clicks) Gaia Tumeric Supreme Extra Strength - 1 cap daily

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Feb 25th afternoon I started feeling pretty yucky. As the evening progressed I had chills, body aches, and fever. I thought I had covid. On the 26th I was worse. on the 27th I went to the ER, and the diagnosis was "unknown virus" I continued to get worse. On March 3rd I called the nurse and she said "I need to go to the ER, don't go to the  ER, go to the closest ER to you". I received the same diagnosis. I thought maybe my CPAP machine had bacteria and they tested for bacteria and it was negative. I went home. On march 8th I was really bad off, I had 103.7 fever still and O2 was 70-80. I was admitted to the hospital. they tested me again and I had bacterial pneumonia. 3 days later they were going to send me home but when I woke up that morning I felt like I had been kicked in the ribs on my right side. I sat in a chair and if I coughed, hiccuped or anything It felt like a knife through my chest. a CT scan showed a massive blood clot in my lung. I was put on medications and I was discharged on March 17th. My left lung had 100% pneumonia and the blood clot was in the right lung and my lungs were unable to help each other. With any exertion, my heart rate jumps and my O2 drops. I can only sit. The theory they had at the hospital is that the Moderna vaccine had the full attention of my immune system which allowed other infections to come into my body unchecked. Since the pandemic started I have left my house on my bicycle to the store and that is it. I have had almost no exposure.
LAB_DATA: yes, see description. will be blood thinners and o2 for the rest of my life.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Upon admission, the patient states he had his first Covid shot 2 days ago.  He had some body aches and arm pain following the injection.  He states last night around 5 or 6 PM he had sudden onset of diffuse upper abdominal pain.  He states when it began it did radiate to his right chest and his neck.  There was no associated nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, or black or bloody stools.  No fever, chills, or sweats.  No cough, nasal congestion, or sore throat.  No shortness of breath or palpitations.   Patient was seen by surgical services and his scan was suggestive of acute cholecystitis.  Patient underwent robotic laparoscopic cholecystectomy by general surgery.  He did not develop any complications.  Patient was able to tolerate regular diet without any significant worsening of his pain so he was discharged home on same day after his cholecystectomy.  He also noted to have AKI which was improving.  He was advised to follow-up with his primary care physician and have a repeat BMP done in 1 week.  He will also need follow-up with surgical services in 2 weeks.
LAB_DATA: Labs showed a white blood count of 10.1, hemoglobin 15, hematocrit 44.4, platelets 216, sodium 137, potassium 4.8, chloride 103, CO2 25, BUN 16, creatinine 1.67, glucose 191, SGPT 43, alkaline phosphate 118, SGOT 19, total bilirubin 0.9, INR 1.05, D-dimer within normal limits.  Chest x-ray was unremarkable.  CT of the chest abdomen and pelvis showed moderate inflammatory stranding around the gallbladder concerning for cholecystitis without cholelithiasis, mild duodenitis, some inflammation of the pancreaticoduodenal groove, hepatic steatosis, and mild atelectasis.  Ultrasound of the gallbladder showed no cholelithiasis or cholecystitis although it was a suboptimal exam.  There was no evidence of biliary ductal dilation.  Patient received IV fluids and pain medications prior to transfer.
HISTORY: Prostate disease stage III, cervical radiculopathy, chronic kidney disease, depression, type II diabetes mellitus, hypertension, hyperlipidemia

Patient received 1st dose of Moderna at approximately 12:30pm on 3/18/21. He did not stay the recommended 15 minutes on site for observation. He drove himself back to vaccination clinic parking lot at approximately 1:40pm and got out of his car hurriedly to get his mask from the trunk before speaking with EMS on site. He then reported to EMS his wife witnessed him have a seizure (eyes rolled back, unresponsive, stiffening of arms and legs) for 2-3 min approximately 1 hour after receiving his shot. He reported when he regained responsiveness he asked his wife what had happened as he reportedly had no recollection of the seizure, they decided to call the patient's sister and she directed them to return to site of vaccination to report his seizure.  EMS who evaluated patient reported he denied (and was not exhibiting) postictal signs/symptoms when he arrived back in parking lot at vaccination site. He denied having a history of seizures or any medical conditions. EMS also reported that neither the patient nor his wife called 911 after the seizure. Patient declined any further medical evaluation/follow up. EMS urged him to call 911 if he had anymore seizure activity to which he replied he thought if he just rested Friday and through the weekend, he'd be fine to return to work on Monday.
LAB_DATA: Called patient to follow up with him today (3/23/21). He reported that yesterday he was feeling dizzy and had experienced a sore arm at the injection site. SYMPTOM_TEXT: ED Visit 3/11/21 History of Present Illness 21 year old man pmhx of autism, recurrent abscesses, presents with complaint of L axilla swelling and drainage. Pt received COVID vaccine in L arm on 3/1. Pt did well until 3/5 when he started to complain of pain in the L armpit. Mother examined the area and did not see anything concerning. The pain continued through the weekend, no fevers. Pt felt warm on Monday, no temperature taken. Mother then noted a few "bump" near the L armpit. The bumps continued to swell and be painful on Tuesday, went to pediatrician and was prescribed Keflex. Pt has been taking Keflex but continues to spike fevers, Tmax 102F on Wednesday. Pt had fevers yesterday and today of "about 100." Pt took a nap today, and woke up with the area draining. Mother states that the drainage was smelly pus. Called PCP who recommended evaluation. ED course: Patient observed in the emergency department of antipyretics and did not have any further fever.  I will switch his treatment to clindamycin and provide topical bacitracin and provide strict criteria to come back if pt became febrile instructions provided to mom.   Patient safe for discharge to home. Discharged in improved condition. Written instructions reviewed with family.  3/18/2021 Discharge Summary History of Present Illness 21yo man with h/o autism and multiple soft tissue infections including cellulitis and pilonidal cyst who presented to the ED 3/13/2021 after axillary drainage and fever.  He had been treated outpatient with keflex, but continued to have fevers at home. Re-evaluated at ED and placed on clindamycin. Cultures from outpatient showing skin flora. Mother has been doing several dressings of drainage at home and ongoing fevers up to 102 so was brought to the ED for evaluation. No cough, rhinorrhea, diarrhea, recent travel, known sick contacts.  Summary of hospitalization: He re-presented to ED on 3/13/2021 and was started on vanc/cefepime/flagyl. A CT scan with contrast done to determine extension of abscess, which was fortunately limited to the subcutaneous plane (no infiltration near bone or into muscle fascia). In the ED, patient's creatinine was 1.5. Patient received IVF and his creatinine downtrended to 0.75 on 3/18/21.   The surgical course was uneventful. Successful debridement of the left axillary abscess was performed on 03/4/21. Wound cultures grew Actinomyces Europaeus and S. Epidermidis and Infectious Disease was consulted. Their antibiotic recommendations to discontinue the cefepime/flagyl and start vanc/CTX were followed. Sensitivity analyses showed S. Epidermidis was sensitive to linezolid, tetracyclin, tigecyclin, bactruim and vancomycin. The Actinomyces Europaeus sensitivities have not yet resulted at time of discharge. Per ID recommendations, the vanc and CTX were discontinued and oral doxycycline was started, which should be continued for 6 months. It could be considered to switch to PO amoxicillin after 2 weeks and finish the 6 month course with amoxicillin. This will be discussed during outpatient follow-up. Per ID recommendations, the following labs should be checked 2 weeks after discharge (on 3/29/21) and could be spaced out to every 4 weeks thereafter if normal: CBC with differential, CRP, ESR, BUN, creatinine, AST, ALT.  The patient is scheduled to see (ID) on 5/5/21. Dermatology was consulted per ID recs for evaluation of spots on the chest and back. Per dermatology these spots are keloid, not suspicious for hidradenitis suppurative, there is no need for biopsy. For pilonidal cyst spot dermatology recommends rec hibicleans cream. Immunology was consulted for recurring abscesses and recommended the following tests, which were ordered, in addition to outpatient followup: IgG, IgA, IgM, IgE, specific Ab titers: for strep pneumo IgG (23 serotypes) and tetanus IgG, lymphocyte subsets, T cell memory panel, B cell memory panel, neutrophil DHR, CH50.  A wound VAC was placed on the left axillary wound bed on 03/15/21 and exchanged on 3/17/21.  Patient tolerated the wound vac changes well with 5mg of oxycodone taken 1 hour prior to the vac change. On 03/18/21 patient was discharged with a home wound vac and VNA.  At the time of discharged patient was afebrile, his pain was well controlled, his oxygen saturations were >94% on room air, he was tolerating a regular diet and voiding/stooling without issues.
OTHER_MEDS: acetaminophen, cholecalciferol, clobazam, diazepam nasal, Depakote ER, lacosamide
CUR_ILL: developmental delay, autism spectrum, epilepsy, recurrent abscesses
HISTORY: developmental delay, autism spectrum, epilepsy, recurrent abscesses

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient at the time of sending him to wait 15 minutes after administering the vaccine was fine. At 5 minutes he began to cough constantly, with nausea, dizziness and feeling really hot in his body. I told him to enter the vaccination room and that we should call 911, which he refused, the patient could breathe and did not lose consciousness at any time. Depo medrol and benadryl 50mg / ml were administered at 11:14 am. blood pressure was taken at 11:20 am 128/87 pulse: 73. Patient began to calm down and feel better little by little. He was given alcohol to smell. At 11:25 am the pressure was taken back to 127/76 and set to 61. He was already starting to feel better. He was told to remain under observation for 20 more minutes, he was with his partner in the chairs waiting for vaccination. At 11:37 am his pressure was taken again 121/79 pulse in 58. He decided to go to bed at home. He was advised to contact his doctor to validate if the second dose should be administered and to go to the emergency room to continue with symptoms. At 2:00 pm, I contacted the patient who had a fever and headache and contacted his pulmonologist to tell him what happened, he told him that he would evaluate if he should take the second dose.
OTHER_MEDS: Medication for asthma, blood pressure and from the psychiatrist

Patient received her first Pfizer dose with no problems. She came back at her scheduled appointment for the second dose of Pfizer. She initially did well, but after 30-40 minutes the patient came back to the pharmacy complaining of chest pain and felt her throat was tightening up. She felt it was from the vaccine and not from any other reason. I asked her if I could call a paramedic and she declined. I asked about calling a family member/ friend and she also declined. I gave her 5ml of liquid Benadryl and asked her to continue sitting in the pharmacy.  After apx. 10-15 minutes she stated she was starting to feel better. I checked on her every few minutes and kept her in my view the entire time. After apx. 30 more minutes she stated feeling a lot better and wanted to go home. I again offered to call someone or call paramedics and she adamantly refused. I gave her some additional Bendadryl to take home with instructions to take 5 ml every 4 hours for the rest of the day. She left the store. After a apx. 5 minutes a technician went out to see if she had left. She spoke to the patient in her car and patient stated she was fine and heading home. She stated she could drive b/c she only lives a couple minutes from the store. I called the patient at home later that night to check on her and she stated feeling fine, and thanked me for checking on her.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Background: Pharmacy received 49 vials of Pfizer COVID vaccine (Lot number EN6199) on 5 March 2021 and stored them in the pharmacy refrigerator.   The doses were labeled with an expiration date of 10 March 2021 at 0701.   Since starting the COVID-19 vaccine program, has always used the doses before they approached the expiration date.  This time, there were 16 vials of the Pfizer vaccine that had not been used and set to expire. The labeled expiration date and time were clearly present on the outside of the bag containing the doses.  On the morning of 10 March 2021, a pharmacist retrieved 1 vial at 0754 and 7 vials at 1138 from that allocation and provided them to nursing for the day?s administrations.  The pharmacy placed those doses in a new amber bag and did not label the bag with an expiration date and time.   The nursing team received the vials, diluted and drew up 20 doses that were administered to patients before 1230.    The charge nurse did not question the expiration date until after 20 patients had been vaccinated.  At that time she messaged the pharmacist to verify the expiration date.  The pharmacist indicated that the label did not state am or pm and misinterpreted the expiration time for the doses as 7:01 PM rather than 7:01 AM.  There was not a defined double check at the time of distribution from the pharmacy to nursing  The remaining 11 vials were quarantined.  The pharmacy manager contacted the manufacturer.  According to Pfizer it?s recommended to use the thawed vaccine within 120 hours, but can be used up to 144 hours.  The doses in question were administered before 125 hours after they were thawed.  The remaining expired vials will be wasted and appropriate notifications sent.  Assessment: Twenty patients received Pfizer COVID vaccine 5 hours passed the labeled expiration date and time.  While exceeding the manufacturer?s recommended beyond use dating, the doses were within the acceptable 144 hours post thaw period and still safe for patient administration.  There was misinterpretation of the labeled expiration time by the dispensing pharmacist, the container of COVID vaccine vials provided to nursing was not labeled with an expiration date or time, there was not a double check on hand off, the nursing team did not double check the expiration date/time before dilution or administration.  Recommendation:  When repackaging COVID Vaccine vials for distribution to vaccination centers, a label including the expiration date and time should be placed on the new container.    When COVID vaccine is transferred from one location or department to the next, a double check of the product, quantity, integrity and expiration date and time may prevent a recurrence of this situation.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Background: pharmacy received 49 vials of Pfizer COVID vaccine (Lot number EN6199) on 5 March 2021 and stored them in the pharmacy refrigerator.   The doses were labeled with an expiration date of 10 March 2021 at 0701.   Since starting the COVID-19 vaccine program, the MOB has always used the doses before they approached the expiration date.  This time, there were 16 vials of the Pfizer vaccine that had not been used and set to expire. The labeled expiration date and time were clearly present on the outside of the bag containing the doses.  On the morning of 10 March 2021, a pharmacist retrieved 1 vial at 0754 and 7 vials at 1138 from that allocation and provided them to nursing for the day?s administrations.  The pharmacy placed those doses in a new amber bag and did not label the bag with an expiration date and time.   The nursing team received the vials, diluted and drew up 20 doses that were administered to patients before 1230.    The charge nurse did not question the expiration date until after 20 patients had been vaccinated.  At that time she messaged the pharmacist to verify the expiration date.  The pharmacist indicated that the label did not state am or pm and misinterpreted the expiration time for the doses as 7:01 PM rather than 7:01 AM.  There was not a defined double check at the time of distribution from the pharmacy to nursing  The remaining 11 vials were quarantined.  The pharmacy manager contacted the manufacturer.  According to Pfizer it?s recommended to use the thawed vaccine within 120 hours, but can be used up to 144 hours.  The doses in question were administered before 125 hours after they were thawed.  The remaining expired vials will be wasted and appropriate notifications sent.  Assessment: Twenty patients received Pfizer COVID vaccine 5 hours passed the labeled expiration date and time.  While exceeding the manufacturer?s recommended beyond use dating, the doses were within the acceptable 144 hours post thaw period and still safe for patient administration.  There was misinterpretation of the labeled expiration time by the dispensing pharmacist, the container of COVID vaccine vials provided to nursing was not labeled with an expiration date or time, there was not a double check on hand off, the nursing team did not double check the expiration date/time before dilution or administration.  Recommendation:  When repackaging COVID Vaccine vials for distribution to vaccination centers, a label including the expiration date and time should be placed on the new container.    When COVID vaccine is transferred from one location or department to the next, a double check of the product, quantity, integrity and expiration date and time may prevent a recurrence of this situation.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Background: pharmacy received 49 vials of Pfizer COVID vaccine (Lot number EN6199) on 5 March 2021 and stored them in the pharmacy refrigerator.   The doses were labeled with an expiration date of 10 March 2021 at 0701.   Since starting the COVID-19 vaccine program, the medical office has always used the doses before they approached the expiration date. This time, there were 16 vials of the Pfizer vaccine that had not been used and set to expire. The labeled expiration date and time were clearly present on the outside of the bag containing the doses. On the morning of 10 March 2021, a pharmacist retrieved 1 vial at 0754 and 7 vials at 1138 from that allocation and provided them to nursing for the day?s administrations.  The pharmacy placed those doses in a new amber bag and did not label the bag with an expiration date and time.   The nursing team received the vials, diluted and drew up 20 doses that were administered to patients before 1230.    The charge nurse did not question the expiration date until after 20 patients had been vaccinated.  At that time she messaged the pharmacist to verify the expiration date.  The pharmacist indicated that the label did not state am or pm and misinterpreted the expiration time for the doses as 7:01 PM rather than 7:01 AM.  There was not a defined double check at the time of distribution from the pharmacy to nursing  The remaining 11 vials were quarantined.  The pharmacy manager contacted the manufacturer.  According to Pfizer it?s recommended to use the thawed vaccine within 120 hours, but can be used up to 144 hours.  The doses in question were administered before 125 hours after they were thawed.  The remaining expired vials will be wasted and appropriate notifications sent.  Assessment: Twenty patients received Pfizer COVID vaccine 5 hours passed the labeled expiration date and time.  While exceeding the manufacturer?s recommended beyond use dating, the doses were within the acceptable 144 hours post thaw period and still safe for patient administration.  There was misinterpretation of the labeled expiration time by the dispensing pharmacist, the container of COVID vaccine vials provided to nursing was not labeled with an expiration date or time, there was not a double check on hand off, the nursing team did not double check the expiration date/time before dilution or administration.  Recommendation:  When repackaging COVID Vaccine vials for distribution to vaccination centers, a label including the expiration date and time should be placed on the new container.    When COVID vaccine is transferred from one location or department to the next, a double check of the product, quantity, integrity and expiration date and time may prevent a recurrence of this situation.

Background: Pharmacy received 49 vials of Pfizer COVID vaccine (Lot number EN6199) on 5 March 2021 and stored them in the pharmacy refrigerator.   The doses were labeled with an expiration date of 10 March 2021 at 0701.   Since starting the COVID-19 vaccine program, the Pharmacy MOB has always used the doses before they approached the expiration date.  This time, there were 16 vials of the Pfizer vaccine that had not been used and set to expire. The labeled expiration date and time were clearly present on the outside of the bag containing the doses.  On the morning of 10 March 2021, a pharmacist retrieved 1 vial at 0754 and 7 vials at 1138 from that allocation and provided them to nursing for the day?s administrations.  The pharmacy placed those doses in a new amber bag and did not label the bag with an expiration date and time.   The nursing team received the vials, diluted and drew up 20 doses that were administered to patients before 1230.    The charge nurse did not question the expiration date until after 20 patients had been vaccinated.  At that time she messaged the pharmacist to verify the expiration date.  The pharmacist indicated that the label did not state am or pm and misinterpreted the expiration time for the doses as 7:01 PM rather than 7:01 AM.  There was not a defined double check at the time of distribution from the pharmacy to nursing  The remaining 11 vials were quarantined.  The pharmacy manager contacted the manufacturer.  According to Pfizer it?s recommended to use the thawed vaccine within 120 hours, but can be used up to 144 hours.  The doses in question were administered before 125 hours after they were thawed.  The remaining expired vials will be wasted and appropriate notifications sent.  Assessment: Twenty patients received Pfizer COVID vaccine 5 hours passed the labeled expiration date and time.  While exceeding the manufacturer?s recommended beyond use dating, the doses were within the acceptable 144 hours post thaw period and still safe for patient administration.  There was misinterpretation of the labeled expiration time by the dispensing pharmacist, the container of COVID vaccine vials provided to nursing was not labeled with an expiration date or time, there was not a double check on hand off, the nursing team did not double check the expiration date/time before dilution or administration.  Recommendation:  When repackaging COVID Vaccine vials for distribution to vaccination centers, a label including the expiration date and time should be placed on the new container.    When COVID vaccine is transferred from one location or department to the next, a double check of the product, quantity, integrity and expiration date and time may prevent a recurrence of this situation.

Approximately 10 minutes after 1st dose of Pfizer vaccination. Pt. was fanning himself, appeared diaphoretic with mask down. He flagged down nurse and reported feeling hot/lightheaded. NP asked for BP machine, instructed patient to take slow deep breaths. Pt. reported he felt like he may lose consciousness. His eyes rolled and he became white/pale and appeared to stop breathing. Code assist called; didn't respond to sternal rub, but raspy breathing, weak/rapid pulse palpated; immediately transferred to the ground level without falling, 2 person assist. 9-1-1 called, BP machine didn't immediately work. As soon as his head was low, his face became bright red and he regained consciousness. He was disoriented briefly but then able to answer questions/oriented. BP elevated, HR 80s. BS 257. No s/s anaphylaxis. Hx of syncope r/t blood draw. Wife present and report hx of DM, HTN, Palpitations. He denied CP/SOB or palpitations. He had eaten and took regular medicine the morning. Paramedic arrived and patient was transported to the nearest ER. Pt. was later discharged.
OTHER_MEDS: Flecainide, Omega 3, Wellbutrin, Vit D, Claritin, Coreg, Jardiance, Magnesium Oxide, Lipitor, Metformin, Atorvastatin, Aspirin
HISTORY: h/o short RP tachycardia (fast-slow AVNRT vs AVRT) on Carvedilol and Flecainide. Episodes of dizziness, h/o syncope related to blood draw, DM, HL, low Magnesium, obesity

Background: pharmacy received 49 vials of Pfizer COVID vaccine (Lot number EN6199) on 5 March 2021 and stored them in the pharmacy refrigerator. The doses were labeled with an expiration date of 10 March 2021 at 0701.   Since starting the COVID-19 vaccine program, the MOB has always used the doses before they approached the expiration date.  This time, there were 16 vials of the Pfizer vaccine that had not been used and set to expire. The labeled expiration date and time were clearly present on the outside of the bag containing the doses.  On the morning of 10 March 2021, a pharmacist retrieved 1 vial at 0754 and 7 vials at 1138 from that allocation and provided them to nursing for the day?s administrations.  The pharmacy placed those doses in a new amber bag and did not label the bag with an expiration date and time.   The nursing team received the vials, diluted and drew up 20 doses that were administered to patients before 1230.    The charge nurse did not question the expiration date until after 20 patients had been vaccinated.  At that time she messaged the pharmacist to verify the expiration date.  The pharmacist indicated that the label did not state am or pm and misinterpreted the expiration time for the doses as 7:01 PM rather than 7:01 AM.  There was not a defined double check at the time of distribution from the pharmacy to nursing  The remaining 11 vials were quarantined.  The pharmacy manager contacted the manufacturer.  According to Pfizer it?s recommended to use the thawed vaccine within 120 hours, but can be used up to 144 hours.  The doses in question were administered before 125 hours after they were thawed.  The remaining expired vials will be wasted and appropriate notifications sent.  Assessment: Twenty patients received Pfizer COVID vaccine 5 hours passed the labeled expiration date and time.  While exceeding the manufacturer?s recommended beyond use dating, the doses were within the acceptable 144 hours post thaw period and still safe for patient administration.  There was misinterpretation of the labeled expiration time by the dispensing pharmacist, the container of COVID vaccine vials provided to nursing was not labeled with an expiration date or time, there was not a double check on hand off, the nursing team did not double check the expiration date/time before dilution or administration.  Recommendation:  When repackaging COVID Vaccine vials for distribution to vaccination centers, a label including the expiration date and time should be placed on the new container.    When COVID vaccine is transferred from one location or department to the next, a double check of the product, quantity, integrity and expiration date and time may prevent a recurrence of this situation.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: No pain at the time of injection. The nurse who gave me the vaccine was very gentle both times. She happened to be the same nurse when I went for both doses. I had a sore arm two days after the first vaccine but that's it. So I expected the same with the second dose. But my arm started to get sore the following evening and furthermore into the night. It felt very warm to the touch and when I finally looked at my bare arm, the injection site was incredibly swollen, red, and there was a white spot where the needle had entered.  The rash looked very lumpy. My arm hurt terribly and it felt like I had been stung by something. But I did not develop any other symptoms. The following morning it was slightly less swollen. Weeks later I still have what looks like a bruise on my arm but I'm fine other than that. My mom and sisters have had the Moderna vaccine without any reaction. They are all  B+ blood type and I'm B- blood type. I don't know if that has anything to do with it. I am also the only one in my family with an autoimmune disease.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient received her second dose of the Modern COVID-19 vaccine at approximately 7:20pm on Tuesday, March 23, 2021. Patient stated after receiving the vaccine that she had a "very long time ago passed out after a blood draw". The patient remained in the chair with her nurse for approximately 2 minutes, her color was good, skin was dry and had normal respiration. The patient then stated "I'm not feeling so well". Patient aware, assisted to floor, lying prone, lost consciousness (called EMS), proceeded to have a seizure, bilateral upper arm postured wrists out, lets still, body tremors. Episode lasted approximately 1 minute. During the episode, airway patent, head protected, respirations spontaneous, pulse regular 90-110. Patient awoke spontaneously, stated was somewhat confused, but making sense was able to voice event leading to episode. Patient spoke with her mother, nurse spoke with her mother to advise patient to be evaluated at the hospital due to seizure. Client and mother agreeable, report to paramedic, client transferred to Hospital by Ambulance with wallet, keys, and phone.

"About 5 min after injection, she came to me asking for Benadryl because her mouth was starting to itch.  So I inject Diphenhydramine 50mg/ml 1ml IM right deltoid and she sat next to me.  After a few minutes, she thought she was feeling better. Then about 5 minutes later she said she could feel her tongue swelling and throat starting to burn, so I called 911 and administered one dose of epi-pen 0.3mg in her right thigh.  She was still able to breathe, talk, and swallow a few sips of water.  Approximately 8 minutes later EMS arrived.  I heard EMS tell her that her blood pressure was good while I was talking to another EMS personnel reporting everything I had done, her husband was there and gave her medical history and other medications she takes (methotrexate, Pristiq, and Renvoq for rheumatoid arthritis and fibromyalgia).  She was taken to the hospital for further examination.  Before hand, she reported no drug allergies and never having any type of allergic reaction to medications, food, or having any adverse reaction to injectable medications.  However, her daughter has many allergies and has used epipens frequently in the past."--Per Immunizing pharmacist.

After I got the shot, on the way home, I started feeling tingling on tongue and lips; had a metallic taste. I felt like I had allergies - I was a little congested - but the next morning, 04:00 am -  I was still congested - and was still breathing short and shallow. I get to work and I'm open mouth breathing - not breathing correctly. It felt like my lungs were swollen on the inside and throat was swollen on inside. Couldn't palpate and feel it but just couldn't access the lower lungs breathing-wise. Started getting dizzy and couldn't think - from 05:00 am to 09:00 am - and I decided I couldn't work anymore. I went to headquarters and I couldn't talk from lack of breathing - would have to stop just to think or just to breathe. I drove by the clinic where I was got my vaccine and decided to go in - I was so dizzy and I realized I shouldn't be driving. They told me to get up and move and I told them I couldn't breathe and I'm not one to say that but they called an ambulance that took me ER. (I was a LPN at one time so I wasn't anxious.)  And they told me it was anxiety - and they kept telling me to breathe. But it wasn't an anxiety attack at all. My heartrate was normal. I was shallow breathing. They gave me a paper bag to breathe into. That's it .I was there for a couple of hours. They had told me to rest. I shouldn't have gotten out of bed that morning - my body just didn't want to move. I felt a little better after a couple of hours and people helped me from there to get home. After that, I felt better - about 4 pm or 5 pm. Second vaccine - felt flu like symptoms for three days after. I still feel a little weird - my bones hurt and I'm achy. Just not feeling right. Note: When I was in the emergency room - my hands were purple. Circulation was weird.They told me my oxygen levels were fine and that I just needed to breathe. It caused carpal tunnel in my wrist - I had nerve damage on that about three weeks - I have about 80 percent nerve damage from previous and so when something irritates it  - it takes a while to recover from it but I have.  I consulted with a doctor about the reaction to first vaccine before getting the second vaccine.
LAB_DATA: EKGs - everything was just fine - at ER
CUR_ILL: three weeks prior - had a cold and was negative for COVID
ALLERGIES: no  except- seasonal type allergies - pollen

On the 16th, I had the right ear and head pain. That lasted Sat, Sun and Mon. I woke up Tuesday morning (18th), I had a small Shingles lesion along with those symptoms. . I went to the doctor's office and saw the NP, who diagnosed me with an ear infection--right Otis externa. On Wed (19th) my right eye was swollen and my scalp, right forehead and eye were covered in shingles. On the 20th, I was diagnosed with having Ocular Shingles. I was put on steroids and sent to an emergent appointment with ophthalmologist because they were concerned that I would lose my sight. He put me on  Acyclovir 800mg, 5 times a day and increased my steroids to: 40mg a day for 2 days, 30mg for 3 days and  20mg for 3 days and 10mg for 4 days. Fortunately the branch that goes into my cornea was not affected. I was in bed the entire time. I still had lesions when I went back to see him, which is why he kept me off work until Feb 1st. I continued to have neuralgia (nerve pain) and then I started itching. I went back to quick care and put on Atarax. I took that every 4 hours for about a week. Then I tapered it down to about twice a day. It eventually got better, but I do itch sometimes.  Looking back, I did have a little right ear pain after the 1st dose of the vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Summary: Abdominal pain (similar to that experienced years previously, but not experienced approx. 2 years previous to Pfizer COVID-21 vaccination) recurred after first vaccination, worsened after second vaccination, leading to 2 ER admission and hospital admission. Ultimate cause still not determined or successfully treated; pain continues treated by opoids, gabapentin, anti-nausea medication.  Patient has not been able to work since March 4th, 2021 (currently March 23rd, 2021).  Details: The day after the first vaccination, abdominal pain similar to that the patient had previously experienced, but which had not presented severely for around a two years, recurred quite severely for 4-5 days.  Missed 2 days of work. Pain reduced enough to resume work after 4-5 days.  The day after the second vaccine dosage (2 Feb 2021), the abdominal pain worsened again, becoming more severe and more prolonged than after the first dosage. Missed four days of work (not consecutive).  Pain worsened. 12 March 2021 visited PCP, who recommended immediate ER/hospital admittance.  ER could not any definite cause of pain (though 8cm fibroid present, thought to be causing lower abdominal pain but not upper abdominal) and released patient.  Abdominal pain became somewhat better but still continued.  March 6th, abdominal pain greatly increased, leading to ER visit and hospital admittance March 6th-March 9th, 2021.  CT scan 6 March 2021.  Relevant results:  Bowel: Multiple dilated loops of distal small bowel with fecalization of small bowel contents and a slow transition to normal caliber at the terminal ileum. The appendix is not visualized. The stomach is unremarkable. The colon is not dilated.   Mesentery/Peritoneum: Small indeterminate density fluid adjacent to dilated loops of bowel in the right lower quadrant.   Nodes: Scattered small abdominal nodes, none meeting CT criteria for pathologic enlargement.   Pelvis: Large uterine leiomyoma.  Uterine fibroid identified as probably source of pelvic and lower abdominal pain.  Mid and upper abdominal pain thought not to be related, however, and may be related to dilated loops of distal small bowel and adjacent fluid.  Pain treated with opoids, gabapentin, anti-nausea drugs, patient released 9 March 2021.  Abdominal pain continues, partially controlled with pain medications.  Lower pelvic pain has not recurred (birth control pills started at end of hospital visit).  Patient has been been able to work since March 4th (currently March 23rd, 2021).  Patient is applying for short-term disability due to extended absence from work caused by these issues.
LAB_DATA: CT scan.  12 Feb 2021. Showed uterine fibroids and dilated ileum similar to 6 March 2021 CT scan. CT scan 6 Mar 2021.  Results:  Bowel: Multiple dilated loops of distal small bowel with fecalization of small bowel contents and a slow transition to normal caliber at the terminal ileum. The appendix is not visualized. The stomach is unremarkable. The colon is not dilated.   Mesentery/Peritoneum: Small indeterminate density fluid adjacent to dilated loops of bowel in the right lower quadrant.   Nodes: Scattered small abdominal nodes, none meeting CT criteria for pathologic enlargement.   Pelvis: Large uterine leiomyoma.  Colonoscopy and endoscopy scheduled for 24 Mar 2021.  Surgery for removal of fibroids is scheduled for April 2021.  The fibroids had been present for several years, now show as 1-2cm larger than before.  Had not been painful previously. Pain is likely related to growth of fibroids and unrelated to vaccine administration (?).  However, the majority of upper abdominal pain and for example, lower right side pain, is believed to be unrelated to the fibroids and increased dramatically after first and second vaccine administration.
HISTORY: Has had general abdominal pain, possible inflammation of ileum, side pain, in the past but a definite diagnosis was never determined and pain and related issues had been minor or absent for many months prior to January 2021 vaccination. (It seems most likely to the patient that the vaccination retriggered these previously existing conditions to a higher level than ever before experienced.)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Not sure if covid vaccine caused this, but this is what happened - Received covid vaccine.  two days later had violent shakes in the night.  Immediately went to get a covid test out of precaution.  Tested negative for covid, but positive for "flu b".  Went home to treat flu with fluids and rest.  Got no better.  Went to heart doctor out of precaution, full work up...everything checked out great.  Went home, got no better.  Went to primary care physician, full work up...found a "spot" on left lung.  Was given antibiotics and steroids, go home and in a few days will be getting better.  3 days later became incapacitated and had to be rushed to ER.  Was admitted into hospital for 6 days to treat "pneumonia".  Also possible UTI and sepsis.  Also while in hospital found out that a mini stroke had happened.  Treatment went well, oxygen levels were good.  Was released with glowing reports.  24 hours later at home had to be rushed to ER again after becoming incapacitated..  Was admitted again  7 more days.  During this time everything took a nose dive in succession.  Lungs were failing, multiple unexplained strokes were happening (while on blood thinners, had been on blood thinner 15 years...after first stroke they changed to another blood thinner...only more strokes).  After so many strokes and compounding of strokes, his neuro function started failing.  He was put on life support.  While on life support his organs started failing.  He had to be put on comfort mode and was dead within 8 hours.  A perfectly healthy 77 year old man who had never been sick a day in his life (literally)  got his 2nd covid shot,  two days later he fell ill.  From that point on his health spiraled out of control until his death on March 19th.  Every doctor (pulmonologist, cardiologist, neurologist, and all attending doctors said that it was "atypical and abnormal" what was happening.  It should not have happened.  180 degrees from normal.
LAB_DATA: None.  He died at the hospital.
OTHER_MEDS: blood pressure medicine, a-fib medicine, thyroid

The patient stated, that on an unknown date in 2011, she had swelling at the injection site and then she "swelled up and had boils on face". She sought medical attention, but no treatment was done. No labs or diagnostic procedures were performed. She recovered form the events on an unknown date.  Later, on 05-MAR-2021, she called to request the ingredients of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). She had difficult reading the documents on the computer due to her age (70-year-old), but did try to read the entire document and did not find the ingredients in zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (also reported as ZOSTERVAX) from 2011 that got from the Health Department.  The patient reported that she reacted to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (also reported as ZOSTERVAX) as she told the person that reported this to the Health Department (in 2011). In the process of getting all her immunizations to the same place of her Health Center, she found that there were no records of reporting what happened to her. She stated "Anyway, I got the results of the 2011 of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (also reported as ZOSTERVAX) vaccine and tetanus "(sp?)"vaccine sent to my new "PA". I relayed on my new "PA", that I got boils that eventually broke and a lot of puss came out, like some huge pimples the size of boils an inch across, besides the pain and they did not seem at all concerned and I am disappointed they did not have a record of my call post-vaccine reactions. Recently, I reported all of this to my new "PA", so they would get the shingles vaccine past due to off my chart". The patient stated that she was currently getting the ingredients for the Coronavirus disease-19 (COVID-19) from other manufacturers and then she would take these to her medical doctor (MD) to make sure there was nothing in these COVID-19 vaccines that she could be allergic to. For that reason, she needed the ingredients of the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (also reported as ZOSTERVAX) to never take those ingredients again.  On 16-MAR-2021, a call to the patient was performed and she stated that 11 years ago, after getting the vaccine, she broke out in boils "all over my face and neck filled with a bunch of puss. I could not leave the house for two weeks." She continued that no physician prescribed this vaccine, and that she voluntarily walked into the Health Department to get the vaccine "because of all of the commercials telling us to get our shingles vaccines." She stated that her new and current health care provider contacted Health Department to follow up on the events, and the health department had no record of her experiencing any side effects. Now, she had concerns about the new COVID-19 vaccines and the ingredients and wanted to know the ingredients that were in the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine. She stated she "finally" had the ingredients for zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) after looking through "pages and pages." She was very concerned with the commercials and advertisements for vaccines that "are not approved." She stated that she "we are lucky that she did not sue the company years ago for her reaction." She stated clearly that she had been asked "4 times" who prescribed the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine and asked why. She was explained about the company Adverse Event Follow-Up process. The patient stated repeatedly she did not want to be contacted again and apologized for "taking out her anger," on me and that she "was clearly not over what happened." She expressed that she was very pleased with customer service and was appreciative. It was reiterated that there was no permission to contact her or her health care provider any further. No additional information was available at this time. The outcome of the event anger was unknown.   The reporter considered vaccination site swelling, pain, vaccination site pain, furuncle and swelling to be related to Zoster Vaccine Live (ZOSTAVAX). Causality assessment with the event anger was unknown.

left arm was bruised, swollen and inflamed also at the injection site; left arm was bruised, swollen and inflamed also at the injection site; left arm was bruised, swollen and inflamed also at the injection site; Sick; scratchy throat; Allergic reaction; rash on chest/ over the next 24 hours the rash spread to her neck and then her mouth 24 hours later; hives on chest; itching; rash spread to her neck and then her mouth 24 hours later; her chest was still blotchy and red for four days/redness/ blotchy; left arm was in pain for a week at the injection site; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of injection site inflammation in a 54-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included red blotches (area starts out blotchy on neck and goes to arms, chest was blotchy and red) and throat irritation (scratchy throat). Previously experienced adverse reactions included allergic reaction to bee sting (Family History) and anaphylaxis (Family History). Previously administered products included Penicillin with an associated reaction of rash macular (received on an unknown date and after shot, the area started out blotchy on her neck and goes to her arms and then a scratchy throat and she just knew something was not right) and Morphine with an associated reaction of rash macular (similar reaction like penicillin). Concurrent medical conditions included drug allergy (to Penicillin and Morphine).   On 28th November 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). In November 2020, 8 hrs after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced rash, hives, pruritus, rash mouth and erythromacular rash. On an unknown date, the patient experienced injection site inflammation, injection site swelling, injection site bruising, injection site pain, sickness, throat irritation and allergic reaction. The patient was treated with antihistamine. On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site inflammation, injection site swelling, injection site bruising, injection site pain, rash, hives, pruritus, rash mouth and erythromacular rash were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the sickness, throat irritation and allergic reaction were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the injection site inflammation, injection site swelling, injection site bruising, injection site pain, rash, hives, pruritus, rash mouth, erythromacular rash, sickness, throat irritation and allergic reaction to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient reported for herself.  The patient received her first dose of Shingrix and she went home and eight hours later she developed a rash and hives on her chest and over the next 24 hours the rash spread to her neck and then her mouth 24 hours later.  The patient had itching and her left arm was in pain for a week at the injection site.  The patient's left arm was bruised, swollen and inflamed also at the injection site. The patient was told by her pharmacy to take an antihistamine which she did and it took 3-4 days for her symptoms to resolve.  The patient had a similar reaction in the past to penicillin and morphine where the area started out blotchy on her neck and went to her arms and then a scratchy throat and she just knew something wasn't right. It took four doses of antihistamine to stop the reaction and her chest was still blotchy and red for four days after. Her symptoms had resolved by the time of reporitng.  The reporter consented to follow up.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Allergic reaction to bee sting; Anaphylaxis; Red blotches (area starts out blotchy on neck and goes to arms, chest was blotchy and red); Throat irritation (scratchy throat)

rash that went from her back halfway down to her tailbone / It was itchy; red mark went to her stomach; itchy hives around the belt area; triangular mark on her arm; had been eating a lot of nuts/food allergy; got a triangular mark on her arm and could not lift it up; eyes looked like they had conjunctivitis but they cleared up; had genital itching; This case was reported by a consumer and described the occurrence of mobility decreased in a 62-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis. The reporter considered the mobility decreased, conjunctivitis, genital itching and skin discoloration to be related to Shingrix. Additional details were provided as follows: Age at vaccination was not reported but it could be 61 or 62 years. The case was reported by the patient for herself. The reporter provided her email address and age but did not want to provide her street address or her date of birth. The patient got Shingrix shot and got a triangular mark on her arm and could not lift it up. The patient did not probe to confirm it was the injected arm however that was the impression she got. Also her eyes looked like she had conjunctivitis but they cleared up. In September 2020 she went to the OB/GYN (Gynecologist) because she had genital itching.  Gynecologist advised to use hydrocortisone topical ointment, she used it for a brief time but it was not working.  The itching went to her shoulders near her bra (brassiere) strap and had a rash that went from her back halfway down to her tailbone. It was itchy and red mark went to her stomach, it was across the stomach and it itched.  The patient thought it was important to mention that it was not just half of her body because she did not think it was a shingles rash because shingles rashes often were on one side of the body only and they may be painful.  The patient said her issue was not just on one half and was not painful. The patient continued to have genital itching and then itchy hives around the belt area.  In November 2020 the patient went back to the doctor (allergist) as the itching had not resolved.  The patient had used a different detergent but that it was a detergent that she had previously used in the past.  But to be cautious she re washed all of those clothes in the original detergent.  The patient had been eating a lot of nuts and asked her doctor if the rash/hives/itching could have been due to a food allergy.  The doctor prescribed Zyrtec, Pepcid, and a different ointment. (She cannot recall the name of the ointment). She was told to use these products for 2 weeks.  After 2 weeks her symptoms had not cleared so she took them for another 2 weeks. For tolerance in 2nd dose refer case US2021AMR060203.; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2021AMR060203:Same reporter, Shingrix 1st dose US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2021AMR061311:Same reporter

The patient previously received the first dose of bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE), via an unspecified route of administration on 2021 (Batch/Lot number was not reported) as a single dose for COVID-19 immunization and did not experience any side effects. This patient was administered the second dose of Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine last Wednesday, 24Feb2021. Starting Thursday, 25Feb2021 she had pain in like the lymph nodes on her right side really bad which was the side she got the Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine second dose in; conductive hearing loss; her ear, side of face and neck on right side hurting really bad. Ear pain is really bad. She took Ibuprofen and it was better but the events continued through Thursday the 25Feb2021, Friday the 26Feb2021 and Saturday the 27Feb2021. Starting Saturday the 27Feb2021 she got ringing in the ears, a tinnitus thing which has been ongoing ever since. Patient also stated, "After the second Covid shot lymph nodes were painful, especially in  my ears, I am hard of hearing, I have hearing loss, conductive hearing loss and when the pain went away I had ringing in the ears for 4 days now and it won't go away." She is not a healthcare professional, but she works in the field of deaf and hard of hearing. She saw that in the beginning people who get COVID can get those symptoms like hearing loss; but she did not know if the tinnitus and conductive hearing loss is associated with the Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine. She has had no other symptoms like that of a cold that would have caused the hearing loss and tinnitus. She called the Pharmacist and ENT and everyone thinks her events are Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine related; but the ENT was only able to tell her that they have only seen people that have COVID that have hearing loss which is considered long term; but the providers have not actually had anyone report hearing loss or tinnitus with the Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine. No one really knows if these events are going to go away. She is about to lose her mind because events won't stop. The ENT read some articles where COVID could affect hearing but did not have information on if Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine could affect hearing. She called to ask for more information about these events relative to the Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine. The patient had read comments for side effects for actually Covid but patient haven't had Covid. Patient had been at home for a year so she has not been exposed to anything, so this is just from the vaccine. She read an article that Covid can affect hearing. Wanted to know if we had reports of that with the vaccine and if it will go away? HCP had seen the article and they know that Covid infection itself can cause it and it is long term but that still being studied so nobody really knows. She could not find any information specific to vaccine as far as the symptoms it comes as a Covid general and then it says long-term and whatever your ear condition is it can worsen. Patient stated that the last time it (ringing) lasted this long was 15 years ago and she needed to go to the hospital and get IV steroids. Therapeutic measures were taken as a result of ear, side of face and neck on right side hurting really bad which included ibuprofen. The outcome of the event ringing in the ears, a tinnitus thing was not recovered, Pain in ear was recovering, while for the other events was unknown. The reporter assessed the events as non-serious.  Information on lot/batch number has been requested.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 15 month old patient received a dose of received Quadracel vaccine in error with no adverse event; 15 month old patient received a dose of received Quadracel vaccine (intended Daptacel) in error with no adverse event; Initial information regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case was received from an other health professional via medical information (Reference number- 00502121).   This case involves a 15 month old male patient who received a 0.5 mL dose of suspect DIPHTHERIA-15/TETANUS/5 HYBRID AC PERTUSSIS/IPV (MRC5) VACCINE [QUADRACEL] [lot number: C5772AA, expiry date: 17-Sep-2022] via intramuscular route at an left thigh for prophylactic vaccination on 02-Mar-201 in error as patient was intended to receive DIPHTHERIA-15/TETANUS/5 AC PERTUSSIS VACCINE [DAPTACEL]) [lot number, expiry date and other dosing details not applicable] (product administered to patient of inappropriate age and wrong product administered). (latency: at the same time of vaccination)  Medical history, medical treatment, vaccination and family history were not provided.  Concomitant medications included PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE CONJ 13V (CRM197) (PREVNAR 13) and HIB VACCINE CONJ (HIB VACCINE CONJ) (HIB-PRPT).  It was a case of actual medication error due to inappropriate age at vaccine administration and wrong product administered.   It was reported that, there have been several patients 15 months of age had been given QUADRACEL and would like to know how safe that was since it was not meant for that age group. Nurse reports that they typically use Pentacel for children's 15-month vaccines.  This 9-month-old child was receiving his 15-month.  The office was out of Pentacel, so the medical assistant (MA) administered HIB-PRPT with QUADRACEL (intended DAPTACEL) and PREVNAR 13.  No adverse effects reported at the time of reporting.  This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holder's compliance with the requirements. The classification as a medical error is in no way intended, nor should it be interpreted or construed as an allegation or claim made by the marketing authorization holder that any third party has contributed to or is to be held liable for the occurrence of this medication error.

At the time of report, the patients experienced no adverse event was reported. Felt fine initially.  About 4 hours later got very light-headed and fainted while walking to rest room - resulted in 7 stitches (head laceration) and 2 broken ribs from fall.  A "vaccident".  I was taken to the ER for treatment and spent 2 nights in the hospital.  Over the next 8 or so hours I experienced fatigue, chills/shakes, nausea (threw up 3-4 times), and fainted a second time (while lying down).
LAB_DATA: Several CT scans (head, chest, spine), arterial ultrasound, EKGs, etc., to assess injuries as well as rule out other possible causes for the fainting.  (I have fainted three times over the past 15 years, so this was not the first episode, though it felt different than the others; usually it has been due to rapid standing up from a lot position.)  A potential contributing factor is dehydration - by the time I was at the ER it was clear that I was VERY dehydrated - they had a hard time finding a cooperative vein.  My wife and I were having dinner and a second (over the course of 2-3 hours) beer at the time as well - but that combo is a typical Friday night in our lives, so there was nothing excessive or unusual.  Just possibly a bad combination together with an unexpectedly strong first dose reaction.
OTHER_MEDS: Omeprezole, misc. daily vitamins, monthly testosterone shots

Thought it was an abscessed tooth at first but later realized that the tooth itself was not really sensitive.  Diagnosed as  trigeminal neuralgia by a nurse practitioner. Have had several smaller attacks since when eating (even though  I am avoiding chewing on left side).  Seems to be set off by hot or cold foods possibly(??).  No noticeable swelling .  The thing is that I have NEVER had this kind of nerve pain in my jaw or anywhere else at all (save for an attack of Shingles 2 yrs ago) .  possibly this is just a coincidence but it seems odd that this occurs two weeks after the injection when my health has been fine thus far.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 18hrs of solid sleep commenced after approx 7hr or wakefulness following vaccination.  Ive been diagnosed with mild  tinnitus for about a decade. I mostly ignore it.  However, about 48hr after shot#1 the volume began increasing... somewhere between 5 and 6 days after it was an 11 out of 10 on volume... so loud I couldn't find words to answer the phone. It comes and goes in waves, I have moments of tolerable racket, and hours of piercing ringing.   Caffeine has no apparent effect for me. I eat a healthy diet, and exercise a couple days per week. I know aspirin can make it worse, but Excedrin has been the only OTC that's ever cut headaches for me, in my life.  Right now I waver between crushing head plain, and undecipherable ringing. Any constant hum like a fan or fluorescent lights is like nails on a chaulkboard to me. Today is day 7,  after a short night, i woke up to crushing head pain, showered and went back to bed, the head pain (without Excedrine) has subsided, giving way to fierce high pitched ringing.   My neck muscles are tired... i just realized Ive been holing the "shudder" pose, shoulders raised to my ears, like one does to protect from a sudden loud noise.
