SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my 2nd COVID19 moderna vaccine on 2/12/21. For 24-48 hours after I had fatigue, poor appetite, fevers (up to 103F), chills, and body aches. On 3/3/21 at around 12:15pm while sitting at my desk, I noticed heart palpitations. I checked by apple watch which said my heart rate was 130. I stepped outside for fresh air, came back to my desk and felt unusual for the rest of the day. I called my PCP who saw me on 3/4/21. EKG in office was normal. Labs checked. Stopped levothyroxine until TSH levels returned. On Monday 3/8/21 PCP called to tell me my TSH was 0.6 (down from 1.3 in 12/2020). Recommended dose change from 75mcg levothryoxine daily to every other day. I took my levothyroxine, felt ok throughout the day, and then at night I was up for 3 hours with heart palpitations. The next day I called my PCP who recommended we go down on the dose to 50 mcg. I got this from the pharmacy and took the dose on Friday, 3/12. After, I developed shaking/tremors, anxiety, palpitations, poor concentration, and overall ill. I saw an endocrinologist who recommended stopping the thyroid medication all together for a couple of weeks. On Monday, 3/15/21 my TSH was 1.49, rest of the thyroid panel was normal, and TPO 81.  I had repeat blood work on 3/22/21 at my TSH was 1.40. In 3 weeks, I have only take 2 doses of levothyroxine/synthroid. A medication I have been on since 2014. Endocrinologist diagnosed mild thyroiditis, recommends no thyroid medication at this time. Will repeat labs in 1 month. Symptoms slowly improving.
LAB_DATA: 12/1/20: CBC, CMP, UA, Lipid Panel, HgbA1c normal. TSH 1.360 3/4/21: CBC, CMP normal. TSH 0.6, Free T3, 1.38 3/15/21 CMP normal. TSH 1.49. Thyroxine (T4) 6.8. T3 uptake 30. Free thyroxine Index 2.0. TPO Ab 81 3/22/21 TSH 1.400

Around 26 hours after the injection the arm pain worsened such that it couldn't be ignored and the axilla pain became very prominent almost worse than the arm pain.  Upon inspection I noticed obvious swelling and pain in my right axilla.  The right arm and axilla pain has persisted and worsened over the last 2 days to now include upper biceps, upper triceps, lower deltoid, trapezius, clavicular and right lateral breast pain.  The axilla and arm swelling has persisted and worsened over the last two days to now include swelling in my upper arm, around my clavicle, my upper chest and upper back.  The initial axilla swelling has not decreased any and is more prominent than any of the swelling located elsewhere.  Of note, I cannot easily palpate any axilla, clavicular or cervical lymph nodes.  If there is lymp involvement the nodes are not appearing to be extremely swollen with palpation exam.

Background: pharmacy received 49 vials of Pfizer COVID vaccine (Lot number EN6199) on 5 March 2021 and stored them in the pharmacy refrigerator.   The doses were labeled with an expiration date of 10 March 2021 at 0701.   Since starting the COVID-19 vaccine program, the MOB has always used the doses before they approached the expiration date.  This time, there were 16 vials of the Pfizer vaccine that had not been used and set to expire. The labeled expiration date and time were clearly present on the outside of the bag containing the doses.  On the morning of 10 March 2021, a pharmacist retrieved 1 vial at 0754 and 7 vials at 1138 from that allocation and provided them to nursing for the day?s administrations.  The pharmacy placed those doses in a new amber bag and did not label the bag with an expiration date and time.   The nursing team received the vials, diluted and drew up 20 doses that were administered to patients before 1230.    The charge nurse did not question the expiration date until after 20 patients had been vaccinated.  At that time she messaged the pharmacist to verify the expiration date.  The pharmacist indicated that the label did not state am or pm and misinterpreted the expiration time for the doses as 7:01 PM rather than 7:01 AM.  There was not a defined double check at the time of distribution from the pharmacy to nursing  The remaining 11 vials were quarantined.  The pharmacy manager contacted the manufacturer.  According to Pfizer it?s recommended to use the thawed vaccine within 120 hours, but can be used up to 144 hours.  The doses in question were administered before 125 hours after they were thawed.  The remaining expired vials will be wasted and appropriate notifications sent.  Assessment: Twenty patients received Pfizer COVID vaccine 5 hours passed the labeled expiration date and time.  While exceeding the manufacturer?s recommended beyond use dating, the doses were within the acceptable 144 hours post thaw period and still safe for patient administration.  There was misinterpretation of the labeled expiration time by the dispensing pharmacist, the container of COVID vaccine vials provided to nursing was not labeled with an expiration date or time, there was not a double check on hand off, the nursing team did not double check the expiration date/time before dilution or administration.  Recommendation:  When repackaging COVID Vaccine vials for distribution to vaccination centers, a label including the expiration date and time should be placed on the new container.    When COVID vaccine is transferred from one location or department to the next, a double check of the product, quantity, integrity and expiration date and time may prevent a recurrence of this situation.

3/16/2021 Reaction from Pfizer second shot:  I received the second Pfizer vaccine on Tuesday, February 23rd, 2021 around 1PM.  Early Wednesday morning I developed Gastric reflux which I never had before. As the day progressed I had severe abdominal pain that lasted throughout the day, also something I never had before. Nausea set in late that evening. Although Thursday was fairly stable, on Friday I developed black diarrhea that continued all day.  By Sunday I was so weak that a nurse came and sent me to hospital via  ambulance. After 4 days of blood tests, transfusions, a chest x-ray, heart monitor, endoscopy and colonoscopy  etc. , the only diagnosis for the significant blood loss was a bleeding ulcer.  This must have been developing on Wednesday when the severe pain began. After release from the 4 day hospital stay, I was sent to our health clinic for 6 days to regain some strength. Since I never had ulcers, I firmly believe that everything was activated on Tuesday when I received the second Pfizer vaccine shot.  Please advise on your perspective of my situation. Is what I have described similar to others who have reported vaccine side-effects?  Thanks and be well.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient initially presented (3/3/21) with headache, fevers, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, myalgias, malaise. Patient related she was in her normal state of health and only started to feel poorly after she received her second COVID-19 vaccination three days earlier.  She interestingly related that after her first Pfizer COVID-19 vaccination she had significant burning in her stomach that she noted but no other major symptoms and notably did not experience this severe burning in her stomach after the second dose. She denied any chest pain, current dyspnea, productive cough, sore throat, urinary symptoms, sick contacts.  She has no history of C. difficile, no recent antibiotics, no recent spoiled foods, no recent travel, no history of radiation.  She does have a history of GERD and has had gastritis with mild gastrointestinal bleeding in the past and undergone EGD negative for H. pylori infection.  She also has undergone colonoscopies with polyps that have been removed and reported as tubular adenomas.  As her hospitalization progressed, she was diagnosed with Severe Sepsis due to E. Coli bacteremia in setting of liver abscess, Cholelithiasis without acute cholecystitis, Atrial Fibrillation with rapid ventricular response, Transaminitis (which resolved). Patient was appropriately treated for these conditions. Also, her known uncontrolled diabetes was treated. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Background: pharmacy received 49 vials of Pfizer COVID vaccine (Lot number EN6199) on 5 March 2021 and stored them in the pharmacy refrigerator.   The doses were labeled with an expiration date of 10 March 2021 at 0701.   Since starting the COVID-19 vaccine program, the pharmacy has always used the doses before they approached the expiration date.  This time, there were 16 vials of the Pfizer vaccine that had not been used and set to expire. The labeled expiration date and time were clearly present on the outside of the bag containing the doses.  On the morning of 10 March 2021, a pharmacist retrieved 1 vial at 0754 and 7 vials at 1138 from that allocation and provided them to nursing for the day?s administrations.  The pharmacy placed those doses in a new amber bag and did not label the bag with an expiration date and time.   The nursing team received the vials, diluted and drew up 20 doses that were administered to patients before 1230.    The charge nurse did not question the expiration date until after 20 patients had been vaccinated.  At that time she messaged the pharmacist to verify the expiration date.  The pharmacist indicated that the label did not state am or pm and misinterpreted the expiration time for the doses as 7:01 PM rather than 7:01 AM.  There was not a defined double check at the time of distribution from the pharmacy to nursing  The remaining 11 vials were quarantined.  The pharmacy manager contacted the manufacturer.  According to Pfizer it?s recommended to use the thawed vaccine within 120 hours, but can be used up to 144 hours.  The doses in question were administered before 125 hours after they were thawed.  The remaining expired vials will be wasted and appropriate notifications sent.  Assessment: Twenty patients received Pfizer COVID vaccine 5 hours passed the labeled expiration date and time.  While exceeding the manufacturer?s recommended beyond use dating, the doses were within the acceptable 144 hours post thaw period and still safe for patient administration.  There was misinterpretation of the labeled expiration time by the dispensing pharmacist, the container of COVID vaccine vials provided to nursing was not labeled with an expiration date or time, there was not a double check on hand off, the nursing team did not double check the expiration date/time before dilution or administration.  Recommendation:  When repackaging COVID Vaccine vials for distribution to vaccination centers, a label including the expiration date and time should be placed on the new container.    When COVID vaccine is transferred from one location or department to the next, a double check of the product, quantity, integrity and expiration date and time may prevent a recurrence of this situation.

I have a history of anaphylaxis, and disclosed that to the medics so they watched me more carefully, which was good, as while I did not experience anything that severe, I did immediately get itchy, turn red and feel quite nauseated. However,  after they monitored me awhile, I told them I felt okay to go home. The next day I had the expected mild flu-like symptoms, which I anticipated. However, what?s been atypical is they returned tenfold three days later. This time with a much higher fever (103), severe chills, fatigue, a seemingly never-ending headache,  muscle spasms,  chest palpitations and suddenly I am experiencing asthma (which is typically seasonal) and am coughing, too.  I?m now a week past when I was vaccinated and each day was feel worse, not better. I have had to cancel my clients and hire a sitter to care for my kids as I am too weak and ill to do it.  I looked up common reactions and nothing states chest pain and/or asthma, nor that it should last this long. That said, as I am high-risk, I work from home and homeschool both of my young kids. Thus, I have been nowhere aside from the vaccine site. Moreover, my partner, our kids and sitter get routinely tested for me,  and everyone is negative. Thus, it appears I am having prolonged, heightened side-effects much more intense than the ?mild? flu-like symptoms otherwise reported, which is concerning. I took no medication prior to receiving the vaccine, either.
HISTORY: Chronic Migraine TMJD Asthma  Seasonal Allergies

Dr. was called with a brief report of these findings and advised that patient was ok to leave and to follow up or to go to Urgent Care if symptoms return or become worse. Patient was provided with these instructions. He verbalized an understanding of information provided him. Patient left ambulatory with no distress noted.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Feb 22,  2021 I had my annual physical with my Primary Care Dr (PCP), and she noticed my CBC panel reflected low platelet count of 67, so she referred me to a specialist and I made an appointment with a hematologist for March 23, 2021. My PCP told me that if I noticed bleeding symptoms that I should go to the ER. I had no previous CBC panels with low numbers.  On March 14, at 1:30am I noticed petechiae on my face, lower abdomen, and back of lower legs and I had been feeling fatigued the previous 2 days. I went to the Hospital ER and they took a total panel and the CBC panel came back with low platelet count of 24. They admitted me to the hospital for treatment and monitoring.   The hospital administered treatment of dexamethasone for 3 days intravenously as well as intravenous immunoglobulin for 2 days. My body and platelet count responded well to the treatment and I was released from the hospital on March 16 around noon.  During the following days from the hospital I experienced severe headaches, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, extreme fatigue, and night sweats until March 20. I still experience extreme fatigue and night sweats.   I had a follow up blood panel on March 19, which showed stabilized numbers. And I had a follow up appointment with Dr to discuss possible causes (one being the covid vaccine due to the temporal relationship) and planning for treatment (follow up blood panel in 2 months and then every 4 months after that to monitor platelet levels).

I slept a total of 17 hours from 6:00 a.m. Saturday to 6:00 a.m. Sunday.  Still achy, feverish, and tired on Sunday.  Rested most of the day.  Monday morning I woke up with icepick headaches in the top left side of my head and the left temple.  These were frequent and intense throughout the day.  No fever but extreme fatigue and still achy in joints.  Injection site is a hard knot and is warm.  Headaches continued Tuesday (yesterday) in same locations in my head.  Still can't taste much, and now have 2 fever blisters on my lips and sores inside on the roof of my mouth.  Wednesday (today) I finally have not had any of the headaches and am slowly regaining my energy.  Still have the sore inside my mouth and can't taste food as it should taste.  Feel much better but not 100% yet.

She was given the Pfizer vaccination in the left deltoid muscle.   During her 15 minute waiting period after the injection, the patient began to experience dizziness and hot. HENT:     Head: Normocephalic and atraumatic.     Mouth/Throat:     Mouth: Mucous membranes are moist.     Pharynx: Oropharynx is clear. No posterior oropharyngeal erythema.     Comments: No swelling of lips or tongue.  Cardiovascular:     Rate and Rhythm: Normal rate and regular rhythm.  Pulmonary:     Effort: Pulmonary effort is normal. No respiratory distress.     Breath sounds: Normal breath sounds. No wheezing or rales.  Skin:    General: Skin is warm and dry.  Neurological:     General: No focal deficit present. She started to get a headache and then all of her joints were starting to hurt.  The next morning, Friday morning she had no energy at all, just felt terrible.  Her face was now swollen, as well as her upper lip.  That night it was getting worse adn worse and her gums were so itchy and all the teeth on the left side felt loose.  It then reached her jaw and then the swelling went to her eye.  She called her PCP, and put on antibiotics, to take a antihystamine and a steroid.  Told her to go to the ER if it did not gete better.  It was horrible by Monday morning, she went to UC and had an abscess in her tooth.  They put her on penicillin, told her not to take the other antibiotics.  By Tuesday morning the swelling had gone down, and the swelling in the gums were also gone, and the teeth were also better.  The abscess was also feeling better.  She had no issues with her gums and teeth prior to this.  By the time she finished the penicillin she was fine.  She went to the dentist and they could not find anything wrong with her, and informed her that it was proof that the vaccine was doing it's job.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 83yo F w/ PMH significant for HTN, chronic thrombocythemia, and glaucoma followed by Heme-Onc without treatment who presented to ED 03/15/21 via EMS complaining of generalized weakness.  She had felt well and had been in her usual state of health, and was able to cook and enjoy a turkey dinner with 5 individuals on 03/07/21, but on 03/08/21 she began to develop progressive generalized weakness up to the point where she remained in bed for several days.  She could not support herself when attempting to rise from bed.  She noted poor PO intake with nausea, no vomiting.  Loose stools for several days, no noted stool blood.  Did endorse waves of lightheadedness and had fallen backwards three times in the prior week, reportedly due to poor balance when standing.  She was unable to elaborate regarding the falls but admitted to hitting her head at least once, unable to say if she lost consciousness or if she felt presyncopal symptoms before falling.  She had initially presented on 03/12/21 to ED for evaluation, workup negative, labs and imaging normal.  CT brain found no acute process.  She was sent home with arrangements for home PT.  She returned to ED 03/15/21 when symptoms had not improved.  In the ED she was found to be afebrile, significantly hypertensive, mildly tachycardic, + orthostatic vital signs.  Labs significant for heme occult positive stool, proBNP 397, WBC 10.1, H/H 13.4/39.9, PLT 493, UA neg for infection.  COVID neg.  CXR found slightly increased interstitial markings.  MRI brain found no acute intracranial abnormality.  She was evaluated by PT and found to be unsafe to DC home as she could not ambulate without leaning backward and to the right and needed 1-2 assist.  She was admitted to HM service for further management.  She has remained consistently afebrile.  She continues to experience significant gait instability, cognitive slowing, and difficulty with finger-to-nose testing with noted dysmetria, no focal weakness.
LAB_DATA: Very modest leukocytosis at times, up to WBC 12.0, last several days ago.  Now about 9 consistently.  CRP elevated since admission (2.03 03/23 up from 0.80).  TSH, random cortisol, B12, folate all normal.  CT brain 03/12 and MRI head 03/15 negative for acute findings.  Teleneurology were consulted and repeat MRI/MRA brain were recommended w/ thinner slicing and coronal DWI to better visualize a possible small stroke; these could not be accomplished until 03/22 due to increasing delirium and need for Anesthesia involvement.  No evidence of acute process by local Radiology.  Images also reviewed by Neurology; also read no acute process.  LP completed 03/23, clear fluid, no orgs or PMS on gram stain but WBC 34 cells/uL, 91% lymphocytes, glucose 48, protein 94, not inconsistent with an aseptic meningitis.  CSF studies: HSV 1/2 PCR neg, cryptococcal Ag neg.  Routine, AFB, and fungal cultures pending.  Also pending from CSF: Enterovirus PCR panel, EBV PCR, Borrelia PCR, Varicella PCR, Listeria Ab.  Serum RPR, Lyme screen negative.  Pending from serum: HSV 1/2 IgM/IgG.  Patient had first of two COVID vaccine doses about 1month ago; unknown relevance.  It is noted from VAERS data that there are more than 800 reports of encephalitis potential linked to COVID vaccination.  Patient denies history of VZV or HSV.  No recent travel.  No pets at home.  Discussed with patient's daughter; she notes patient was previously alert, conversant, and independent.  She is significantly changed, though appears somewhat better every day.  She reports no family members have taken ill recently.  Started acyclovir 10mg/kg q8h IV 03/23.  Discussed with ID, who consulted 03/24. They note, from an ID perspective, presentation does not fit very well with an aseptic meningoencephalitis, which is what CNS fluid analysis might point to. They noted it would be reasonable to discuss w/ Teleneurology any other potential non-infectious causes which might explain her clinical presentation plus mild lymphocytic predominant CSF abnormalities.  Given negative HSV1/2 CSF PCR, they recommended discontinuation of acyclovir, d/c'd 03/24.  Updated hospital.  They note technically this appears to be an aseptic meningitis by lab findings; a viral or autoimmune encephalitis remain in the differential.  It is noted that the patient does have a positive serum ANA screen at 1:80, speckled pattern.  They recommend adding oligoclonal band profile to CSF, as the presence of CSF banding would suggest intrathecal antibody synthesis and point toward autoimmune etiology.  They also recommend serum autoimmune encephalitis panel (ARUP test code 2013601; ordered), SPEP, as well as CSF encephalitis panel if possible; unfortunately, per lab, there is no CSF remaining for study.  EEG also recommended, as this could elucidate features suggestive of viral meningitis.  EEG ordered.  TeleNeuro Dr requests update through TeleNeuro portal of any significant findings.  He notes that the autoimmune encephalitis panel takes days if not more to result and, if this is thought to be possibly an autoimmune encephalitis, then an in-person Neurology assessment would be needed to evaluate for possible empiric start of immune-modulating therapy.  If in line with patient and family goals of care, then the patient could potentially be transferred to hospital for this.  Dr. will be on service until Monday 03/29 so he will be available for ongoing discussions as needed.

About 30 minutes after receiving COVID-19 vaccine by Janssen, patient reported having an itchy throat and some feeling swollenness in her throat. Pharmacist asked if she could breathe and she confirmed she can. Pharmacist asked if she would like to be administered IM injection or oral version of diphenhydramine and patient requested IM version. Pharmacist administered diphenhydramine 25mg intramuscularly and monitored for response where patient reported feeling better and less swelling and itchiness. Patient requested an additional dose due to incomplete resolution of symptoms and about 2-3 minutes later, pharmacist administered an additional dose of diphenhydramine 25mg intramuscularly. Pt was monitored for about 40 minutes until her spouse came to pick her up. Patient was advised to contact her provider and potentially request and epinephrine pen for on-hand use. Pharmacist found a pharmacy, CVS, that carried the epinephrine pen and informed patient where that was so she could inform her provider where to call in the script. Patient left premises reporting feeling like she could breathe fine and no swelling upon leaving the store. The store also provided patient with a box of diphenhydramine (Benadryl) oral tablets to take with her as well as a bottle of water. Her spouse took her so she would not need to drive after feeling potentially drowsy upon injection of diphenhydramine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: No treatments initially. Big chills in the evening of March 20 and difficulty breathing, 100.7 F fever by morning, inability to even sit on March 21 so I stayed mostly in bed, nausea, headache, sore throat, altered taste (things tasted bitter and as chalk), strong body aches. I  understand that the fever was not high, so my extreme weakness and exhaustion were not really related to the fever. Fever subsided by March 22, but numbness on the whole  left side of head and body appeared  for about 2 hours in the evening - unpleasant and scary, but I did not seek intervention. Headache and nausea on March 23 and 24. Total inability to sleep on the night of March 23/24 (stabbing headache and nausea contributed to a lot of anxiety). Finally took Xanax in the morning of March 24, so I finally slept between 7:30 and 10:30am. I am writing this at 3:30 pm on March 24. I am much better compared with March 21, but still with a significant headache and some nausea.   I had Covid-19 in the first half of November. Post-vaccine symptoms were similar to my covid symptoms, but quick. In December I got post-covid a-fib and was diagnosed with heart failure. Improved on medication, awaiting heart ablation in May 2021. I am concerned that with the strong reaction I felt  after the first dose, my reaction after the second dose may be even worse than that on March 21.

Monday, the swelling came back  - hands,  lower legs and on my face and the hair loss came back. The fever was gone but the night sweats lasted for about a week (with no fever.)  I am still having some of the hair loss but the worst of it was for those initial 2-3 weeks. The swelling in my hands/face etc lasted about 2 weeks. Two weeks after vaccine, I lost my sense of taste - I can taste some things but not other things. Bone aches from fibromyalgia is still bad. Last Friday, I took Tylenol before I went to bed and I was fine. I am still a little swollen and I'm still taking the Lasix.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient came in to get her second COVID shot. informed me that she had reactions to the first (lymph node swelling, hives, bells palsy symptoms, and nausea). Her doctors and specialists discussed it with her and agreed they wanted her to have the second dose. She had pneumonia twice, had covid and has residual effects from it, and had mono. They were unsure if the symptoms were directly from the immunization or the fact that she had mono/pneumonia when she got it and didn't know. I Gave her the immunization and she said she felt warm after it. I sat with her for 30 minutes and she said she felt flushed and itchy, she was given 10 ml of Benadryl 12.5mg/5ml. She had no visible hives or swelling at the injection site or on her chest or arms. She felt nauseous and took her own phenergan. After sitting for 45 minutes together she said she wanted to go home. She went shopping for a few things and checked in before she left. I told her if there was any swelling at all in her throat/face or if she felt like she couldn't breathe to call 911 or get to the hospital immediately. She said she would and I will call tomorrow to follow up with how she is feeling.
HISTORY: HAD COVID, HAD MONO AND PNUEMONIA WITHIN THE PAST MONTH, DIABETES

I told the monitor, and she brought the nurses over. The nurses took me to a different location for monitoring. I took some benadryl at about 12:45 pm. This event happened on 3/20/2021. On 3/21, I was physically and emotionally drained. I still had a slight pressure going down my chest. On 3/22, I went to work and developed a headache and was nauseous and my stomach was cramping by 10am. I went to the allergist at 3pm. She told me to take non-PEG liquid benadryl and Pepcid AC. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hospital Course:  Patient was admitted 2 days after having received his COVID-19 vaccine and had SIRS including hypotension.  Was believed to be a possible reaction to the vaccine.  He was admitted to the ICU and briefly he needed vasopressors.  The hypotension resolved and did not recur.  An echocardiogram showed that he had a moderate pericardial effusion, cardiology saw him and does not believe that this contributed to the hypotension.  He also thought his stools were dark however he has had quite dark stools for many years he told me, ever since he was started on iron pills.  He could not confirm whether or not the stools might be a little darker than usual for him and he also had 1 out of 3 stool occult blood test that were positive.  He has chronic anemia with the hemoglobin slightly lower than his baseline, so GI was consulted and an EGD was performed.  He does have Barrett's esophagus and GI discussed with him how he will need follow-up EGDs, and I reminded him of that as well.  Warning signs and alarm symptoms were discussed.  He was placed back on his Eliquis however he will not be taking the Effient medication.  This was based on recommendation from cardiology.  He will have lab work done and see his primary care provider within several days.  He will also have a video capsule test done and pick this up either today or tomorrow and follow-up in several days with GI.  Discussed going back on his low-dose Eliquis with GI.  Discussed with cardiology and GI and discussed with the patient the risks, benefits and alternatives.  He will watch for any signs of bleeding and stick with a low dose of Eliquis.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 5-7 minutes of getting the vaccine, I felt a cold sensation in my brain followed by a tingly sensation in my face, sick on my stomach, dizziness and feeling faint. My husband told me to lean by in my chair, and I did. For a minute or two I felt slightly better, but then it started again; my stomach hurt, I felt dizzy and felt like I was going to faint. My husband got out of the car and went to get the paramedics. When they arrived, they asked me if I could walk to the tent. I knew I had to because I knew I was in trouble. When I got to the tent, I sat down and told the paramedics I was going to faint, and I did. When I regained consciousness, I threw up twice. The paramedics put a heart monitor on me, (from what my husband told me) they took my blood sugar, (I heard the paramedic say the result, and I told him I was not a diabetic). They put an IV in me, and gave me fluids, (from what my husband told me). They sent me by ambulance to ER. In the ED, I told the doctor what happened. She said what happened were not the side effects of the vaccine. After lying supine for sometime, I started to feel the same symptoms again; sick on my stomach, dizziness and feeling like I'm going to faint. I called out for someone. When the doctor came in, I told her I was starting feel the same way as before. She said my labs were great, and they were ready to discharge me; but I could stay if I wasn't ready to go. I told her I trusted her judgement, and was discharged. Throughout the day, I had the same symptoms, but did not faint again.
OTHER_MEDS: I starting taking Valacyclovir for a herpes outbreak 10 days prior to my vaccine and stopped taking it 3 days before getting the vaccine.

I got home, ate breakfast and then began logging in for work and the nausea grew.  Around 11:30 am, I felt tired and the need to lie down, which I did for a while, then around 20 minutes later, I got up to go to the bathroom, feeling like I was going to vomit and have diarrhea.  When I stood up, I felt really lightheaded, managed to only remove my pants and then got in the tub where I could lie down.  I vomited  (once) and had diarrhea for I don't know how long.  At some point I was able to sit up and use my handheld shower to rinse off and get back to bed where I slept until about 4:30 pm.  No more nausea although I am playing it safe and eating crackers and drinking ginger ale.  I feel better now.  Not sure it this was related to not eating and taking my antidepressant, food poisoning, or the vaccine.  But felt I should report.

Thanks for listening.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received 1st Moderna dose 02/23/2021. Noticed small scaly bumps in the small of my back about 3 days after shot. The bumps continued to mulitply and then on 3/11/2021, I removed my clothes for nightly shower to discover that my trunk on both sides were covered in small, dark bumps/welts.  No itching, no oozing, no pain. They were sensitive to touch but not unbearable. Freaked out because what had started in the small of my back had now spread to my trunk. Went immediately to emergency room where ER doctor diagnosed as shingles, but I told him this made no sense as I had been twice vaccinated against chickenpox (elementary school and upon entry into USAF; but also that I had never had chickenpox nor been exposed to anyone who had it or shingles. He then diagnoses as folliculitis - but again I told him this made no sense, because it had spread from my back to my front. I told him that the only new "thing" that had been introduced into my system was the 1st dose of Moderna to which he finally admitted he had no clue about any side effects from from any of the vaccines.  I took my 2nd dose yesterday 3/23/2021 and am 32 hours in. Besides the aches and slight fever, I have noticed that the bumps/welts have returned and are turning red. They had begun to resolove and were turning dark brown and going away.  I was prescribed Vibramycin and Predinisone and also counseled to get a skin biopsy, but I have not heard back from the hospital. My healthcare comes through the VA here.   I have photos from the first incident and have just taken new photos an hour ago for comparison and contrast and would be happy to share these with the CDC. *Please note: I do not have the lot/batch number for 2nd dose. The Health Department did not/does not provide this information at the time of vaccinations. We have to call back down to get this.

The evening of the inkection I felt nauseated. The next morning I had fever and chills (100 F) and fatigue. The next morning I had lymphedema on the rt side of my jaw and down my anterior neck. The next day I developed a large ulcerated area at the back of my throat on the right with intense ear pain. I went to the clinic and a covid test was done (I don't have the results yet). Today (7days after the injection) I returned to the clinic because  my throat ulcer had gotten larger and spots were appearing on the roof of my mouth. I again ran a low grade fever. I was again diagnosed with either a viral infection or an unusual immune response to the vaccine.
LAB_DATA: Covid test done on Monday March 22 - 4 days after my second injection. (no result yet). I wish they had swabbed my throat for strep throat but they didn't.
HISTORY: None - although I had an acute episode of septic shock one year ago - which occurred during a stent placement for nephrolithiasis, hydronephrosis and pyelonephritis.  Three months later I had a spontaneous pneumothorax of my rt lung. Unknown if these were related. I am otherwise remarkably healthy.
ALLERGIES: Intolerances to eggs, dilaudid, levaquin, fosamax

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This was my first dose of the vaccine.  12 hours after injection I had chills so bad my teeth chattered, head ache, body aches, temperature of 101.7, weak and very fatigued for 24 hours. I went through 6 treatments of chemotherapy for ovarian cancer last year and this vaccine response was every bit as bad as chemo!

CUR_ILL: Finished chemotherapy for ovarian cancer Nov 4, 2020.  On Letrozole now for maintenance therapy.

He was admitted on 3/5/21 with COVID-19 pneumonia which progressed to severe disease. Patient died on 3/21/21 attributed to COVID-19. Patient had underlying B cell follicular lymphoma, previously on chemotherapy. Reported does not feel patient's hospitalization or death was attributable to the vaccines, however following FDA Emergency Use Authorization, "The vaccination provider is responsible for mandatory reporting of the following to the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS): vaccine administration errors whether or not associated with an adverse event, serious adverse events* (irrespective of attribution to vaccination), cases of Multisystem Inflammatory Syndrome (MIS) in adults and children, and cases of COVID-19 that result in hospitalization or death."

Weakness Narrative:  Patient is a 61 year-old female with PMH of multiple sclerosis. She received her first COVID vaccine on 1/14/21 and her second dose on 2/4/21. Denied any serious reaction to first dose of vaccine. She had a visit with her spinal cord injury reaction to first dose of vaccine. She had a visit with her spinal cord injury psychiatrist via VVC on 2/24 following a fall that day due to extreme weakness and edema in her legs. On 3/9 she called her primary care provider office with continued symptoms, reporting extreme weakness and inability to ambulate beyond a couple steps since receiving COVID vaccine on 2/4. She additionally reported believing these issues to be related to her MS. It was noted by her provider that her symptoms did not appear to be different than prior symptoms and that she was treated for UTI at her last hospital admission (which can cause pseudoexacerbation of her MS). Patient was instructed to report to the ER for evaluation and was admitted to the medical facility 3/15. As a diagnosis, she was noted to have lower extremity weakness secondary progressive MS vs chronic deconditioning and lower extremity lymphedema. She was treated for her MS and discharged 3/18.

Trouble breathing  Narrative:  Patient presented to the ED 2 days after first dose of COVID vaccine  with a pruritic rash as well as trouble breathing. He reported the rash which was  urticarial and quite pruritic was generalized, ranging from his face over his neck  and back. Initially he had little relief from diphenhydramine, but after a second  dose the rash was largerly resolved. Patient denied chest tightness, wheezing,  tongue or lip swelling. He did not report any GI symptoms, fevers, mild myalgias  but only with a slight headache. No loss of taste or spelled sensation. The rash  most prominent on the right forehead raised a suspicion of herpes zoster which  could also cause a headache, but ED provider ruled this out because patient had  received his herpes zoster vaccination. The rash was also not painful although  bilateral and asymmetric. ED physician concluded it to be a mild reaction to the  vaccine. Patient was discharged on H1 and H2 blockers (diphenhydramine and  famotidine)

nausea, syncope sent to ED, not admitted Narrative: 35 yo FEMALE with a history of anaphylaxis to penicillin in her younger years, received her first shot of the Pfizer vaccine earlier today. Approximately 10 minutes after receiving the injection, she felt a sense of lightheadedness, associated with mild nausea, but no shortness of breath or  difficulty swallowing. The next thing she knows, the nurses were standing at her side and she was on the floor. she was seen by the attending staff to look somewhat pale, and have a brief episode of arching of her back before she was lowered to the ground. She did not fall out of the chair onto the ground. There was no subsequent tonic-clonic activity, and the patient did not lose consciousness per the nursing staff in attendance. Concern for the possibility of anaphylaxis the staff administered epinephrine 0.3 mL intramuscular. Upon ED evaluation, the patient appeared to have had a mild vasovagal reaction to her injection. No evidence this was anaphylaxis. A 12-lead EKG was performed which revealed a normal sinus rhythm, with a ventricular rate of 69bpm. Intervals, durations and QRS axis were normal, with no diagnostic ST segments. With further observation there was no concerning symptoms and was discharged home.

On an unknown date, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. The patient received their second of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number: 044A21A) on 10 Mar 2021 in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. The batch number of first dose is mentioned as 00M20A.   The patient experienced stroke about a week ago, between the first and second dose. She stated she wasn't sure, but she went to the hospital over the weekend. She also stated that she was not speaking well. The medically significant event is stroke. Open magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) was performed but no results were provided. Treatment for the events was not known.   Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the event(s) was not applicable. SYMPTOM_TEXT: generalized weakness and difficulty with ambulation; fever; Systemic Inflammatory Response Syndrome; intermittently confused with situation; walked with unsteady shuffling gait; PR (Heart rate) was 110 bpm; incoherent (neurological problem); woke up several times to void at night; chills; disoriented to time, place and event; A spontaneous report was received from a physician concerning a 65 year old  male patient  (race, ethnic group unknown)  who received Moderna's COVID-19 Vaccine (mRNA-1273), and experienced systemic inflammatory response syndrome (systemic inflammatory response syndrome), generalized weakness and difficulty with ambulation (asthenia), fever (pyrexia), woke up several times to void at night (nocturia), was incoherent- neurological problem (incoherent), was disoriented to time, place and event (disorientation), walked with unsteady shuffling gait (gait disturbance), his PR (heart rate) to 110 bpm (tachycardia) and chills (chills).  The patient's current condition included metastatic small cell lung cancer, diabetes, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, fatigue, loss of appetite and shortness of breath. On 22 Jul 2019, patient had stroke. On 02-Aug-2019, patient underwent left carotid endarterectomy. Concomitant medications reported included are Jardiance (empagluflozin), losartan potassium, atorvastatin calcium, aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid), ondansetron, tramadol HCl, Tylenol (paracetamol), promethazine, robitussin DM (dextromethorphan hydrobromide, guaifenesin), xanax (alprazolam), benadryl (diphenhydramine hydrochloride), colace (docusate sodium), famotidine, prochlorperazine and dulcolax (bisacodyl).  On 12 Feb 2021, prior to onset of events, the patient received his second of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number: unknown), for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  On 12 Feb 2021, after administering the vaccine, the patient developed fever, chills and woke up several times to void at nighttime. Patient's wife stated that he was incoherent (neurological problem) on 13 Feb 2021 and was hospitalized on the same day. He was hospitalized for fever, generalized weakness and difficulty with ambulation. In emergency department he was disoriented to time, place and event, sometimes confused with situation and walked with unsteady gait. The reporter also reported that on 12 Feb 2021, patient was diagnosed with event systemic inflammatory response syndrome, grade 3.    Laboratory tests were performed, on an unknown date, the patient's heart rate was 110 bpm, blood pressure was 128/66. On 13 Feb 2021, COVID-19 test result was negative, influenza type A was negative and influenza type B was negative, urinalysis was negative for bacteria blood (peripheral) culture and no growth was seen in urine culture.  Patient was treated with fluids, ceftriaxone, tylenol and metoprolol.  On 14 Feb 2021, patient was discharged from the hospital.   The outcome of the event systemic inflammatory response syndrome was recovered and the events generalized weakness and difficulty with ambulation, fever, waking up several times to void at night, incoherent- neurological problem, disoriented to time, place and event, walking with unsteady shuffling gait, increased heart rate and chills were unknown.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Further information has been requested.

On 17 Feb 2021, few days after administering the vaccine, the consumer experienced vertigo related nausea and vomiting. The patient was hospitalized for two days and experienced a blood clot during hospitalization. Patient was treated with only diazepam on first two days of treatment. In hospital, patient was given meclizine, diazepam and other anti-nausea medication whereas at home, patient was treated with ondansetron 8 mg, meclizine and diazepam.   On 05 Mar 2021, the patient received the second of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch no- 036A21A), intramuscularly in the left upper arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  The action taken with the second dose of mRNA-1273 in response to the event was not applicable.  The outcome of the events, vertigo, nausea, vomiting was not recovered whereas the outcome of blood clot was unknown at the time of the report.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

Treatment for the events included unspecified antibiotics.  Action taken with second dose of mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported. The event, inappropriate schedule of product administration, was considered recovered/resolved.; Reporter's Comments: Although a temporal association exist, and there is lack of patient's medical history and list of concomitant medications, based on the known risk and etiology of liver abscess, the events are assessed as unlikely related to mRNA-1273 administration.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Passed out /Lost all awareness; Light-headed; Hyperventilating; He caught his breath; Elevated heart rate; Tingling sensation; He was unable to form cohesive sentences; Muscles movements were impeded; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient).   A 23-year-old male patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (Pfizer-Biontech Covid-19 Vaccine, Lot. EN6206) single dose, in the left arm, on 08Mar2021, at 11:45 AM, for COVID-19 immunisation. The patient had not received any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the BNT162B2 vaccine. The patient had not received any other medications within 2 weeks. Relevant medical history and concomitant medications were unknown. No known allergies were reported. The patient had not experienced COVID-19 prior vaccination. On 08Mar2021, at 12:00 PM, 5 minutes after vaccination, the patient became very light-headed. In a few seconds his vision went dark and he passed out. After an unknown amount of time, he became semiconscious and was hyperventilating. While hyperventilating, his eyes were open, but he could not see anything. Once he caught his breath, after about 15 seconds, his vision came back and he lost all awareness of where he was. After about 30 seconds, the patient realized he was in the observation area for the facility and alerted the medical professionals near his vehicle he was sitting in. Medical professionals checked his vitals, which were fine other than an elevated heart rate, and he had a tingling sensation over his body for the next two minutes. In this time, he was unable to form cohesive sentences, and his muscles movements were impeded. It took another 40 minutes to return to a relatively normal state. No treatment was received. The patient recovered from the adverse events. Post the vaccination, the patient has not been tested for COVID-19.  No follow up attempts are possible. No further information is expected.

On an unspecified date in Sep-2020, within a week after receiving Flucelvax Quadrivalent, the patient could not kneel down, bend his knees and his thumb was aching. On Wednesday, March 17, the symptoms were the same as Tuesday, March 16 in the morning, but numbness and tingly subsided. On Thursday, March 18, the swelling, numbness and tingly in the fingers and hands returned when I woke up at 4:00 am. My symptoms have not changed throughout the day. On Friday, March 19 after midnight, I went to the emergency room regarding to the pain of swollen fingers and hands (entire palm), numbness and tingly feeling. I was prescribed with 4 mg of methylPrednisolone for 6 days and to taper down. SYMPTOM_TEXT: In the week following my vaccination, I presented no symptoms. After day 7, I developed soreness/tenderness in my left armpit and a series of neurological symptoms that are very concerning including depression, anxiety, insomnia (accompanied with heart racing, sweating, tingling in extremities, obsessive thoughts etc). Although, I have had sleep issues during the course of the pandemic, I do not deal with daily anxiety. I very rarely have to turn to any medication and especially have not had any  anxiety symptoms or sleep issues recently.   I do not believe the CDC has commented on the connection between vaccine safety and any relationship between vaccine immune response and neuropsychiatric disorders. Or how antibodies produced via vaccine react to other proteins.  My daily activities have been significantly impacted over the course of this week.  I would appreciate learning if there is possible cross-reactivity and if that has presented in other adults.
LAB_DATA: I plan to get blood work done next week and continue consulting with my doctors.

The patient is a healthy 32 yo with a history of  AE after Pfizer Covid vaccine #2 (lot #EL1284, receipt 06 January). She reports receipt of vaccine at about noon. She developed nausea about 30 minutes later. She developed headaache about 1-1 1/2 hours later. She fetl lethargy and fatigue about 4-5 pm and was asleep by 18:00. She slept through until noon the next day when her mother awoke her due to concern for her breathing pattern. She said she felt exhausted and unwell like 'a terrible hangover'. She could not stand and her limbs felt weak and flaccid. Family called the nurse help line who instructed to call EMS. She was soaked in sweat, but no fever and reports she was told her BP was elevated, her extremities were numb but tingled as they improved, and she recalls very severe headache and breathing was hard due to feeling 'heavy'. She felt better as she got near the hospital. She notes her recall of the events is hazy. She was treated with IVF and Toradol and discharged with tylenol, motrin and zofran. She denies emesis, but recalls severe myalgias, knee arthralgias which continued with fatigue for about 10 days, and still has discomfort to her right knee. She reports chest tightness with exertion, which resolved. She denies cough, diarrhea, or any immediate reaction suggestive of IgE. She reports local site reaction of erythematous plaque with smaller peripheral macules, centrally located at the injection site with smaller macules peripherally down her arm.  She denies history of AE with other vaccines.  Per ER notes, states EMS report HR 114, diaphoretic, HTN,, febrile, tachypneic, received 500 cc bolus. Triage states crying, anxious and tachypnic, guided in deep breathing,  BP 95/65, HR 100, RR 26  sat 97%, T 98.3; documented as ill appearing. cc: fatigue, weakness, sweating, nausea, malaise, headache. Only diagnostic is EKG which was normal. She was treated with Ofirmev, in addition to IVF and Torrodol.
LAB_DATA: Only diagnostic is EKG which was normal.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: He received his vaccine, and immediately he could taste it in his mouth. As the month went on it got worse and worse.  In March he was out cleaning up the yard and as he worked it got worse and worse.  He would have to work for 5 and sit down for a minute.  He has hyperventilation syndrome and diagnosed back in 1980 and has been under control, this is one thing that always happens, which seems to be an ongoing problem that he's having.  His settings on his pacemaker seem to be OK.  He was sitting on his couch and watching a race on 3/8/21 and got a shock coming up from the bottom part of his head, through his chest and out through his right eye, this was less than 2 seconds.  This was an event, but not a hard "mule" kick event.  He wasn't doing anything to get the shock.  The defibrillator is connected to the bottom part of his heart.  He has a logic system and had an episode of 190-200 BPM which was at the top part of his heart.  He had all of his equipment checked out yesterday, but they could not give him an answer why he got a shock.  He now has to set up an appointment with his cardiologist to see tomorrow.   He has had the pacemaker for 6-7 years now and the device goes into the device clinic and he gets reports regarding this information.   They device people said there was no registration that he had any event.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 27 year old male received his second shot today and immediately after the shot felt nausea lightheaded and dizzy. He says it feels like the room is spinning around him. He does not have any PMH nor does he state that he takes any medication. He denies any street or illegal drug use. Pt states that he had a couple drinks last night and did not eat anything today. After providing water and laying him down for 30 min he was still symptomatic so it was decided that the patient should be seen in the ED for further workup. Patient is in agreement and he will be sent.   148/101, P 92, O2% 99% 150/101, P 90  ED Note: Physical exam reveals an alert, normocephalic male he has a normal heart rate with normal heart sounds, normal pulmonary effort, lung sounds are clear abdomen is soft he does have some tenderness in the epigastric area no rigidity or distention is noted.  Patient is neurologically intact he is alert and oriented x3, able to ambulate unassisted with a normal gait, sensation is intact, strength is 5 out of 5 in both upper and lower extremities bilaterally, no pronator drift, cerebellar function intact with finger-to-nose and heel-to-shin test.  Posterior oropharyngeal area shows uvula is midline there is no swelling airway is patent.   This is an atypical presentation if the patient is actually having an reaction to the vaccination however I am also concerned for possible abdominal issue we will work him up for ACS as well.  We will give patient a dose of Benadryl to see if that helps with some of his symptoms Bentyl for the stomach cramping and spasming and some fluids.   Lab work was unremarkable patient had a negative troponin's EKG was negative for STEMI, ischemic changes T wave abnormalities, lactate was normal, lipase was normal.  Patient still complaining of abdominal spasms but states he is feeling better than when he first arrived and would like to go home.  Patient states that his abdominal spasms have happened intermittently over the last few years he has had multiple imaging of his stomach and that he feels comfortable being discharged with the intention that if anything worsens he would return here to the emergency department.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Saturday, February 20, 2021 I received my first dose of Moderna Lot# 024M20A. I was detained for 30 minutes due to having a sulfa allergy and then released. There were no concerns that day. My arm was very sore, which I was aware of could happen for a couple of days and then things seemed to clear up.  Sunday, February 28th, I woke up at 5 in the morning with a severe red, itchy rash that covered my arms, legs, chest, back, and scalp. I took Benadryl every 4 hours until 8pm in which symptoms grew worse and I drove myself to the Emergency Department.  Upon examination, the doctor diagnosed that this was a rash for nonspecific skin eruption. I was administered dexAMETHasone sodium phosphate (PF) (Decadron, EPINEPHrine (Adrenalin), and famotidine (Pepcid) at 10:32 pm. The epinephrine was supposed to relieve symptoms within thirty minutes and was administered into my left upper arm. It did not. They informed me that the steroid they gave me would take an additional 4-6 hours to kick in and would last 2-3 days. After detaining me to observe my body's reaction to the medicine; I was released approximately at 11:30 pm. They told me to continue taking Benadryl. At the end of the visit my vitals were as following: blood pressure: 113/69, weight 205 lbs, temperature 98.2 degrees F, pulse 91, respiration 18, oxygen saturation 99%.  I was only able to sleep 3 hours that night, wake up off and on due to severe inflammation and horrible itching.  Due to the lack of relief by the provided medication I began taking lukewarm oatmeal baths combined with cool showers every hour to help alleviate the itch. This helped to make the itching less strong but did not alleviate it all together. In between showers (no soap) I applied Calamine lotion and aloe vera lotion on every other rotation. These combined efforts helped to keep me from scratching as much as possible.   I was not able to go to work on Monday (3/1/21). Throughout the day of Monday, I continued to take repeated showers, baths, and apply lotion. I continued to take Benadryl as directed on the package. My rash did not seem to be clearing up and I was just able to make the itching slightly bearable. This continued through the night, where yet again I was only able to sleep 2-3 hours.  On Tuesday morning (3/2/21) I awoke with my back inflamed and hopped immediately into a cold shower. Upon my husband?s examination the rash suddenly had worsened. There were more breakouts of tiny itchy spots everywhere and the itching was unbearable.  As soon as Urgent Care opened at 8:00 am I checked myself in. My primary care physician was unable to secure me an appointment for the day and I couldn?t take it any longer. At this point I was so uncomfortable I started to feel helpless and hopeless.   I was seen by the PA-C at approximately 8:20 am. I informed the doctor that I had not had any changes to my diet, my medications, my laundry detergent, dish soap, body wash, lotions, toothpaste, deodorant, perfume, or any other thing of that nature. I had not been sick this year at all and I had not had any other vaccinations nor traveled outside of the country. Nor have I been quarantined this year because of Covid. I also told about my good friend in. She stated that exactly the same amount of days later after her Covid shot; she had a rash too but her rash disappeared after a couple of days and she did not need medical care for it nor was it itchy. I informed the doctor that the only thing I had that was new to my body was the first dose of the Moderna vaccine. It was the doctor's opinion that this was an allergic drug rash. The doctor also firmly recommended that I do not get the second dose of the Modern vaccine. He said that there have been credible reports released of delayed reactions such as this and even though there wasn?t a way yet to medically prove it, due to all of the information provided he strongly felt this was a reaction to the vaccine. My rash was so bad that as he lifted my shirt to look at it, even he was appalled.   I was administered methylPREDNISolone sodium succ (PF) (SOLU-Medrol) in the buttocks at 9:03 for treatment. I was also prescribed a predniSONE 50 mg tablet to take once daily with food for the next 8 days. Additionally I was prescribed triamcinolone 0.5% ointment to apply 2-3 times daily as needed for itching relief. I was released at approximately 10 am after an observation period to make sure I did not have a reaction to the methylPREDNISolone sodium succ (PF) (SOLU-Medrol). Upon my release I was given a doctor?s note to not return to work until Thursday 3/4/21. I was told to keep taking Benadryl along with the new medication to treat the rash. Approximately around noon hours later, I noticed an improvement in the rash on my arms. They were less spotty, inflamed and itchy. By 5 pm my legs were improving and were less itchy and spotty as well. I picked up my predniSONE prescription at 5:30 and took 1 tablet by mouth with food at approximately 6pm.  By late evening, the itching on my back, chest, and scalp had decreased by 50% although they were still majorly broken out. I did not take any more oatmeal baths but I did take a cool shower before bed using no soap.   On Wednesday 3/3/21 I awoke at 7 am. I was able to sleep through the night and only woke up twice to reapply aloe vera lotion. My arms and chest were no longer itchy but my back, scalp, shoulders, and behind my knees were still itchy. I was still very broke out on my chest and back but the skin did not appear to be as inflamed. My arms are no longer red and the spots are very tiny and pink. I picked up my triamcinolone 0.5% ointment at 10 am in the morning due to the pharmacy needing to order it. At approximately 11:30 am I canceled my 2nd dose appointment with that was scheduled for Friday, March 19th at 1:50 pm.   Thursday 3/4/21 I returned to work. I found myself to be very weak and very shaky if I stood for any amount of time. I had to work with students from my rolling chair, scooting around the classroom.  Sunday 3/7/21 I seem to have my strength back and am no longer shaky when I am trying to do daily tasks.  Thursday 3/11/21 It?s a week later and the bumps are finally  mostly cleared up. Half a dozen remain on my shoulders and have turned into pus filled bumps almost like pimples.   Thursday 3/25/21 All traces of the bumps are gone from my arms, legs, chest, and back. Only a couple of them remain now appearing to have turned into ?pimples?. My doctor prescribed me a steroid cream to help get rid of the remaining bumps.
OTHER_MEDS: buspirone 10 mg  hydroxyzine 10mg lamotrigine 100 mg melatonin 3 mg quetiapine 100 mg
HISTORY: Arthritis, Bipolar, PTSD, General Anxiety Disorder

Within 5-minutes of vaccination, the patient reported weakness and confusion. EMS evaluated the patient on-site. No signs of stroke. EKG demonstrated NSR, rate 77bpm, no ST elevation. FSBG was 290mg/dl. EMS transported the patient to Hospital Emergency Department. Enroute, the patient became increasingly confused, forgetting their birthday and location. Patient was hypertensive (178/104) and reported a "crushing headache". EMS crew became concerned for stroke. In ED, the patient remained hypertensive (178/93). ED Physician had high suspicion of TIA versus acute reaction to COVID-19 vaccine. Administerd 650mg acetaminophen and 1mg Lorazepam. Admitted patient to critical care unit where patient stated they had developed a sudden-onset diffuse banding-like headache with associated nausea, diaphoresis, blurry vision, and confusion. MRI was negative and patient was transferred from ICU to hospital. Hospital physician believed the symptoms were likely a vagal mediated response or reaction to his COVID vaccination. Patient was discharged on 3/20 with diagnoses of TIA, Acute encephalopathy, Insulin-dependent type 2 diabetes, Essential hypertension, CAD, Unspecified mood disorder, Dyslipidemia, Obesity, and Mild neuro cognitive disorder

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient vaccinated with first dose of Pfizer with subsequent infection and hospitalization due to COVID-19 infection. Initial H&P reads in part as,  "Patients symptoms began on or around Thursday 3/11 when he began to feel  fatigued. After two days of fatigue, he presented to an urgent care facility on  Saturday 3/13. He was noted to have a fever there and was diagnosed with a  presumed UTI, though patient reports at bedside that he has not had any  dysuria. He was treated with nitrofurantoin and increased his furosemide  temporarily per urgent care's recommendations. He then presented to the ER  on 3/15 with continued fatigue and a low blood pressure at home. We were unable  to clarify the method by which the blood pressure measurement was obtained  and/or if it was repeated. Antibiotics were changed to cephalexin at that time  despite a relatively clear UA. His daughter brought him back to the ER today  (3/18) due to persistent issues with low grade fevers in the 100-100.5 range,  significantly worsening fatigue, anorexia, and oxygen levels of 92-93% on  nonproductive cough. Does not have a home O2 requirement. In addition, he  endorses feeling chilled during the admission evaluation. Denies any chest pain,  nausea, vomiting, fevers, diarrhea, constipation. # Fever Progression of symptoms from Saturday 3/13 may constitute original presentation  of Covid-19. Presentations on 3/13 and 3/15 with dyspnea and fatigue. Initially  thought to be UTI and was treated with nitrofurantoin and cephalexin. UA on 3/15  in ED was negative for leuk esterase and nitrites. Tested positive for covid-19  on 3/18 with lymphopenia, 90-92% on room air. No home O2 req. Given duration  of symptoms and worsening fatigue and fevers, will admit for treatment of Covid- 19. Also considered CHF exacerbation, COPD exacerbation as explanations for  dyspnea. Possible CHF exacerbation as well given 1+ bilateral pitting edema to  mid-shin and JVD to ear lobe. Suspicion for COPD is low given no report of  increased sputum production and questionable history in chart to begin with.  Would be beneficial to clarify history with collateral history 3/19."

03/22/2021 - 12:43PM:  A 30mcg/0.3mL dose* of COVID-19 Pfizer BionTECH vaccine was drawn up into a 1mL syringe with a 23G 1? needle and prepared for administration in the left deltoid.  This was the patient?s second dose of a 2 dose series.           [*vaccine lot EN6207] After insertion of the needle into the left deltoid, the nurse was beginning to depress the plunger into the barrel of a needle-syringe combination, (to administer a 0.3mL dose of COVID-19 Pfizer BionTECH vaccine) when the needle and hub broke from the tip of the syringe.  The needle hub effectively spooned the vaccine to splash in the reverse direction from that of the needle. The vaccine went into the nurses left eye and surrounding facial area(s).  The needle and hub remained in the patient?s arm, but it was removed immediately with no adverse effect, bleeding, or leaking of the vaccine suspension. The nurse apologized to the patient who was to receive the vaccine.  She told him that no vaccine was injected.  She said she would immediately prepare another 0.3mL dose of COVID-19 Pfizer BionTECH vaccine and **repeat the administration.    The man gave no vocal expression of refusal or display of guarding.  Following the completed IM injection of a 0.3mL dose of COVID-19 Pfizer BionTECH vaccine, the patient was reported to express his wish that she make ?a note of what happened.?  He was escorted to a post-immunization monitoring area for the recommended 15 minutes of observation.  During this time he did not report any adverse effects, or other abnormal outcomes possibly associated with the vaccine administration.

I waited onsite in my car for the recommended 10 minutes. Feeling fine, I drove away. I stopped at an Aldi about 7 minutes away to use the restroom and get a snack, as I had been at the fairgrounds for about an hour and had not had breakfast. While washing my hands, I noticed that my chest and neck were flushed red, much like when I drink certain alcoholic beverages. My left arm was also red up to my elbow. Feeling a little concerned, but still feeling generally okay, I bought a Snickers bar and a Coke, thinking it would perk me up. I checked out at 10:39AM, and got on the highway to head for home. I drank a bit of Coke, then took a bite of my candy bar. It felt a little weird when I swallowed, but went down okay. I took two more small bites, and each was more difficult to swallow than the last, with the third one not clearing the back of my throat without several sips of Coke to wash it down. I was starting to feel panicky, but figured response time would be relatively slow, as I was traveling in between jurisdictions. I remember my late  husband giving me Benadryl after I had a weird reaction to a flu vaccine in 2014, so I focused on getting to a store down the road where I could stop quickly for some. This took another 5 minutes from where I was. I bought a box of Benadryl Liqui Gels, and took one in the parking lot. I could still breathe, so I decided to drive home to my daughter, who was home alone. The Benadryl kicked in when I was almost home, so I did not call EMS.
PRIOR_VAX: Flu Vaccine 2014, inflammation at site, tested positive for Lupus, although I have not tested positive since.
ALLERGIES: Codeine, sesame seeds, shrimp, and alcohol.

After being administered the vaccine at 7:12 am, when the nurse stood me up and started to walk me to the holding area, I became dizzy, my legs got weak, and there was a loud ringing in my ears. I nearly collapsed as I reached the seat in the holding area they were taking me to. I placed one 0.5MG tablet of my prescription Alprazolam in my mouth and waited for the nurse to bring water. They took me via wheelchair from the holding area to a secluded spot behind a curtain. There, I laid on a cot, received cold water, and a nurse talked to me while I recovered. It felt like I was having an anxiety attack, which has never happened to me after getting a shot before. Fitbit heart rate data shows my heart rate at 105 BPM at 7:00 am (going through the admission process, walking around the facility), 83 BPM at 7:10 am, 79 BPM at 7:15 am, 74 BPM at 7:20 am. Between 8:15 am and 1:25 pm, my heart rate remained between 63 and 89 BPM. My arm was sore and my skin hurt (an issue that I have when I feel very stressed). Additional symptoms arose around 1:35 pm. SYMPTOM_TEXT: He received his vaccine, had a sore arm and that evening around 7 hours later it was as if a switch flipped he was not able to breath, and his wife noticed on his body she could see all his veins like a track on his trunk and everywhere.  He could not talk.   He said that he was burning up, was hot and clammy.  He got in the shower to cool himself down, and was told that the oxygen was not getting to where it was supposed to go.  His wife called 9-1-1 and the EMT's said that his oxygen had dropped down into the 60's. He went to the hospital and they said he had pulmonary edema that filled his lungs that quickly.  He was not intubated, and is on a BiPAP.  He was given Lasix, steroids, antibiotics trying to pull the fluid off of his lungs.  He has had so many different scenarios from people at the hospital right now and at one time one of his nurses said that his blood work showed a possible blood clot.  They looked at his lungs and they said that they did not see it in his lungs.  Then they said that he had a heart attack and that he needed a valve replacement.  Today, 3/25/21 they told him that he did not have a heart attack, did not need a valve replacement.  Last night they said that his BP was dangerously high and today, his BP is fine.  He also had an adverse reaction to the steroids and had a ROID rage from that as well giving the nurses and his wife a hard time, hanging up the phone on her, and said that he was leaving the hospital.   He was fine prior to the vaccine, and does not have any other issues for him to have this reaction.  He is in ICU and they keep saying that they are going to put him in a cardiac care unit.  He has a lot of IV lines and his 2nd COVID test came back negative.   He feels like they are just running test to get money out of him.  They said that he may be able to go home tomorrow.
